d. The driver put out his hand and carefully drove the bee into an air stream that blew it out of the window. \'93Croppers going fast now,\'94 he said. \'93One cat\'92 takes and shoves ten families out. Cat\'92s all over hell now. Tear in and shove the croppers out. How\'92s your old man hold on?\'94 His tongue and his jaws became busy with the neglected gum, turned it and chewed it. With each opening of his mouth his tongue could be seen ipping the gum over. \'93Well, I ain\'92t heard lately. I never was no hand to write, nor my old man neither.\'94 He added quickly, \'93But the both of us can, if we want.\'94 \'93Been doing a job?\'94 Again the secret investigating casualness. He looked out over the elds, at the shimmering air, and gathering his gum into his cheek, out of the way, he spat out the window. \'93Sure have,\'94 said the hitch-hiker. \'93Thought so. I seen your hands. Been swingin\'92 a pick or an ax or a sledge. That shines up your hands. I notice all stu like that. Take a pride in it.\'94 The hitch-hiker stared at him. The truck tires sang on the road. \'93Like to know anything else? I\'92ll tell you. You ain\'92t got to guess.\'94 \'93Now don\'92t get sore. I wasn\'92t gettin\'92 nosy.\'94 \'93I\'92ll tell you anything. I ain\'92t hidin\'92 nothin\'92.\'94 \'93Now don\'92t get sore. I just like to notice things. Makes the time pass.\'94 \'93I\'92ll tell you anything. Name\'92s Joad, Tom Joad. Old man is ol\'92 Tom Joad.\'94 His eyes rested broodingly on the driver. \'93Don\'92t get sore. I didn\'92t mean nothin\'92.\'94 \'93I don\'92t mean nothin\'92 neither,\'94 said Joad. \'93I\'92m just tryin\'92 to get along without shovin\'92 nobody around.\'94 He stopped and looked out at the dry elds, at the starved tree clumps hanging uneasily in the heated distance. From his side pocket he brought out his tobacco and papers. He rolled his cigarette down between his knees, where the wind could not get at it. The driver chewed as rhythmically, as thoughtfully,