cause he just done it for ducks. He wasn\'92t puttin\'92 on no dog.\'94 The driver was reassured. He knew at least that Joad was listening. He swung the great truck viciously around a bend and the tires shrilled. \'93Like I was sayin\'92,\'94 he continued, \'93guy that drives a truck does screwy things. He got to. He\'92d go nuts just settin\'92 here an\'92 the road sneakin\'92 under the wheels. Fella says once that truck skinners eats all the time\'97all the time in hamburger joints along the road.\'94 \'93Sure seem to live there,\'94 Joad agreed. \'93Sure they stop, but it ain\'92t to eat. They ain\'92t hardly ever hungry. They\'92re just goddamn sick of goin\'92\'97get sick of it. Joints is the only place you can pull up, an\'92 when you stop you got to buy somepin so you can sling the bull with the broad behind the counter. So you get a cup a coee and a piece pie. Kind of gives a guy a little rest.\'94 He chewed his gum slowly and turned it with his tongue. \'93Must be tough,\'94 said Joad with no emphasis. The driver glanced quickly at him, looking for satire. \'93Well, it ain\'92t no goddamn cinch,\'94 he said testily. \'93Looks easy, jus\'92 settin\'92 here till you put in your eight or maybe your ten or fourteen hours. But the road gets into a guy. He\'92s got to do somepin. Some sings an\'92 some whistles. Company won\'92t let us have no radio. A few takes a pint along, but them kind don\'92t stick long.\'94 He said the last smugly. \'93I don\'92t never take a drink till I\'92m through.\'94 \'93Yeah?\'94 Joad asked. \'93Yeah! A guy got to get ahead. Why, I\'92m thinkin\'92 of takin\'92 one of them correspondence school courses. Mechanical engineering. It\'92s easy. Just study a few easy lessons at home. I\'92m thinkin\'92 of it. Then I won\'92t drive no truck. Then I\'92ll tell other guys to drive trucks.\'94 Joad took a pint of whisky from his side coat pocket. \'93Sure you won\'92t have a snort?\'94 His voice was teasing. \'93No, by God. I won\'92t touch it. A guy can\'92t drink liquor all the time and study like I\'92m goin\'92 to.\'94 Joad uncorked the bottle, took two quick swallows, recorked it, and put it back in his pocket. The spicy hot smell of the whisky lled the cab. \'93You\'92re all wound up,\'94 said Joad. \'93What\'92s the matter \'97got a girl?\'94 \'93Well, sure. But I want to get ahead anyway. I been training my mind for a hell of a long time.\'94 The whisky seemed to loosen Joad up. He rolled another cigarette and lighted it. \'93I ain\'92t got a hell of a lot further to go,\'94 he said. The driver went on quickly, \'93I don\'92t need no shot,\'94 he said. \'93I train my mind all the time. I took a course in that two years ago.\'94 He patted the steering wheel with his right hand. \'93Suppose I pass a guy on the road. I look at him, an\'92 after I\'92m past I try to remember ever\'92thing about him, kind a clothes an\'92 shoes an\'92 hat, an\'92 how he walked an\'92 maybe how tall an\'92 what weight an\'92 any scars. I do it pretty good. I can jus\'92 make a whole picture in my head. Sometimes I think I ought to take a course to be a ngerprint expert. You\'92d be su\'92prised how much a guy can remember.\'94 Joad took a quick drink from the ask. He dragged the last smoke from his raveling cigarette and then, with callused thumb and forenger, crushed out the glowing end. He rubbed the butt to a pulp and put it out the window, letting the breeze suck it from his ngers. The big tires sang a high note on the pavement. Joad\'92s dark quiet eyes became amused as he stared along the road. The driver waited and glanced uneasily over. At last Joad\'92s long upper lip grinned up from his teeth and he chuckled silently, his chest jerked with the chuckles. \'93You sure took a hell of a long time to get to it, buddy.\'94 The driver did not look over. \'93Get to what? How do you mean?\'94 Joad\'92s lips stretched tight over his long teeth for a moment, and he licked his lips like a dog, two licks, one in each direction from the middle. His voice became harsh. \'93You know what I mean. You give me a goin\'92-over when I rst got in. I seen you.\'94 The driver looked straight ahead, gripped the wheel so tightly that the pads of his palms bulged, and the backs of his hands paled. Joad continued, \'93You know where I come from.\'94 The driver was silent. \'93Don\'92t you?\'94 Joad insisted. \'93Well\'97sure. That is\'97maybe. But it ain\'92t none of my business. I mind my own yard. It ain\'92t nothing to me.\'94 The words tumbled out now. \'93I don\'92t stick my nose in nobody\'92s business.\'94 And suddenly he was silent and waiting. And his hands were still white on the wheel. A grasshopper ipped through the window and lighted on top of the instrument panel, where it sat and began to scrape its wings with its angled jumping legs. Joad reached forward and crushed its hard skull-like head with his ngers, and he let it into the wind stream out the window. Joad chuckled again while he brushed the bits of broken insect from his ngertips. \'93You got me wrong, mister,\'94 he said. \'93I ain\'92t keepin\'92 quiet about it. Sure I been in McAlester. Been there four years. Sure these is the clothes they give me when I come out. I don\'92t give a damn who knows it. An\'92 I\'92m goin\'92 to my old man\'92s place so I don\'92t have to lie to get a job.\'94 The driver said, \'93Well\'97that ain\'92t none of my business. I ain\'92t a nosy guy.\'94 \'93The hell you ain\'92t,\'94 said Joad. \'93That big old nose of yours been stickin\'92 out eight miles ahead of your face. You had that big nose goin\'92 over me like a sheep in a vegetable patch.\'94 The driver\'92s face tightened. \'93You got me all wrong\'97\'94 he began weakly. Joad laughed at him. \'93You been a good guy. You give me a lift. Well, hell! I done time. So what! You want to know what I done time for, don\'92t you?\'94 \'93That ain\'92t none of my aair.\'94 \'93Nothin\'92 ain\'92t none of your aair except skinnin\'92 this her