ell, when Uncle John woke up in the mornin\'92 he slaps another leg in the oven. Pa says, \'91John, you gonna eat that whole damn pig?\'92 An\'92 he says, \'91I aim to, Tom, but I\'92m scairt some of her\'92ll spoil \'92fore I get her et, hungry as I am for pork. Maybe you better get a plate an\'92 gimme back a couple rolls of wire.\'92 Well, sir, Pa wasn\'92t no fool. He jus\'92 let Uncle John go on an\'92 eat himself sick of pig, an\'92 when he drove o he hadn\'92t et much more\'92n half. Pa says, \'91Whyn\'92t you salt her down?\'92 But not Uncle John; when he wants pig he wants a whole pig, an\'92 when he\'92s through, he don\'92t want no pig hangin\'92 around. So o he goes, and Pa salts down what\'92s left.\'94 Casy said, \'93While I was still in the preachin\'92 sperit I\'92d a made a lesson of that an\'92 spoke it to you, but I don\'92t do that no more. What you s\'92pose he done a thing like that for?\'94 \'93I dunno,\'94 said Joad. \'93He jus\'92 got hungry for pork. Makes me hungry jus\'92 to think of it. I had jus\'92 four slices of roastin\'92 pork in four years\'97one slice ever\'92 Christmus.\'94 Casy suggested elaborately, \'93Maybe Tom\'92ll kill the fatted calf like for the prodigal in Scripture.\'94 Joad laughed scornfully. \'93You don\'92t know Pa. If he kills a chicken most of the squawkin\'92 will come from Pa, not the chicken. He don\'92t never learn. He\'92s always savin\'92 a pig for Christmus and then it dies in September of bloat or somepin so you can\'92t eat it. When Uncle John wanted pork he et pork. He had her.\'94 They moved over the curving top of the hill and saw the Joad place below them. And Joad stopped. \'93It ain\'92t the same,\'94 he said. \'93Looka that house. Somepin\'92s happened. They ain\'92t nobody there.\'94 The two stood and stared at the little cluster of buildings. Chapter 5 The owners of the land came onto the land, or more often a spokesman for the owners came. They came in closed cars, and they felt the dry earth w