aid, \'93Can\'92t think of that. Got to think of my own kids. Three dollars a day, and it comes every day. Times are changing, mister, don\'92t you know? Can\'92t make a living on the land unless you\'92ve got two, ve, ten thousand acres and a tractor. Crop land isn\'92t for little guys like us any more. You don\'92t kick up a howl because you can\'92t make Fords, or because you\'92re not the telephone company. Well, crops are like that now. Nothing to do about it. You try to get three dollars a day someplace. That\'92s the only way.\'94 The tenant pondered. \'93Funny thing how it is. If a man owns a little property, that property is him, it\'92s part of him, and it\'92s like him. If he owns property only so he can walk on it and handle it and be sad when it isn\'92t doing well, and feel ne when the rain falls on it, that property is him, and some way he\'92s bigger because he owns it. Even if he isn\'92t successful he\'92s big with his property. That is so.\'94 And the tenant pondered more. \'93But let a man get property he doesn\'92t see, or can\'92t take time to get his ngers in, or can\'92t be there to walk on it\'97why, then the property is the man. He can\'92t do what he wants, he can\'92t think what he wants. The property is the man, stronger than he is. And he is small, not big. Only his possessions are big\'97and he\'92s the servant of his property. That is so, too.\'94 The driver munched the branded pie and threw the crust away. \'93Times are changed, don\'92t you know? Thinking about stu like that don\'92t feed the kids. Get your three dollars a day, feed your kids. You got no call to worry about anybody\'92s kids but your own. You get a reputation for talking like that, and you\'92ll never get three dollars a day. Big shots won\'92t give you three dollars a day if you worry about anything but your three dollars a day.\'94 \'93Nearly a hundred people on the road for your three dollars. Where will we go?\'94 \'93And that reminds me,\'94 the driver said, \'