ll be aroun\'92,\'92 I says. \'91I\'92ll be aroun\'92 till hell freezes over. There ain\'92t nobody can run a guy name of Graves outa this country.\'92 An\'92 they ain\'92t done it, neither.\'94 Joad said impatiently, \'93Where\'92s my folks? Tell about you standin\'92 up to \'92em later, but where\'92s my folks?\'94 \'93Well, they was gonna stick her out when the bank come to tractorin\'92 o the place. Your grampa stood out here with a rie, an\'92 he blowed the headlights o that cat\'92, but she come on just the same. Your grampa didn\'92t wanta kill the guy drivin\'92 that cat\'92, an\'92 that was Willy Feeley, an\'92 Willy knowed it, so he jus\'92 come on, an\'92 bumped the hell outa the house, an\'92 give her a shake like a dog shakes a rat. Well, it took somepin outa Tom. Kinda got into \'92im. He ain\'92t been the same ever since.\'94 \'93Where is my folks?\'94 Joad spoke angrily. \'93What I\'92m tellin\'92 you. Took three trips with your Uncle John\'92s wagon. Took the stove an\'92 the pump an\'92 the beds. You should a seen them beds go out with all them kids an\'92 your granma an\'92 grampa settin\'92 up against the headboard, an\'92 your brother Noah settin\'92 there smokin\'92 a cigareet, an\'92 spittin\'92 la-de-da over the side of the wagon.\'94 Joad opened his mouth to speak. \'93They\'92re all at your Uncle John\'92s,\'94 Muley said quickly. \'93Oh! All at John\'92s. Well, what they doin\'92 there? Now stick to her for a second, Muley. Jus\'92 stick to her. In jus\'92 a minute you can go on your own way. What they doin\'92 there?\'94 \'93Well, they been choppin\'92 cotton, all of \'92em, even the kids an\'92 your grampa. Gettin\'92 money together so they can shove on west. Gonna buy a car and shove on west where it\'92s easy livin\'92. There ain\'92t nothin\'92 here. Fifty cents a clean acre for choppin\'92 cotton, an\'92 folks beggin\'92 for the chance to chop.\'94 \'93An\'92 they ain\'92t gone yet?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Muley. \'93Not that I know. Las\'92 I heard was four days ago when I seen your brother Noah out shootin\'92 jack-rabbits, an\'92 he says they\'92re aimin\'92 to go in about two weeks. John got his notice he got to get o. You jus\'92 go on about eight miles to John\'92s place. You\'92ll nd your folks piled in John\'92s house like gophers in a winter burrow.\'94 \'93O.K.\'94 said Joad. \'93Now you can ride on your own way. You ain\'92t changed a bit, Muley. If you want to tell about somepin o northwest, you point your nose straight south-east.\'94 Muley said truculently, \'93You ain\'92t changed neither. You was a smart-aleck kid, an\'92 you\'92re still a smart aleck. You ain\'92t tellin\'92 me how to skin my life, by any chancet?\'94 Joad grinned. \'93No, I ain\'92t. If you wanta drive your head into a pile a broken glass, there ain\'92t nobody can tell you dierent. You know this here preacher, don\'92t you, Muley? Rev. Casy.\'94 \'93Why, sure, sure. Didn\'92t look over. Remember him well.\'94 Casy stood up and the two shook hands. \'93Glad to see you again,\'94 said Muley. \'93You ain\'92t been aroun\'92 for a hell of a long time.\'94 \'93I been o a-askin\'92 questions,\'94 said Casy. \'93What happened here? Why they kickin\'92 folks o the lan\'92?\'94 Muley\'92s mouth snapped shut so tightly that a little parrot\'92s beak in the middle of his upper lip stuck down over his under lip. He scowled. \'93Them sons-a-bitches,\'94 he said. \'93Them dirty sons-a-bitches. I tell ya, men, I\'92m stayin\'92. They ain\'92t gettin\'92 rid a me. If they throw me o, I\'92ll come back, an\'92 if they gger I\'92ll be quiet underground, why, I\'92ll take couple-three of the sons-a-bitches along for company.\'94 He patted a heavy weight in his side coat pocket. \'93I ain\'92t a-goin\'92. My pa come here fty years ago. An\'92 I ain\'92t a-goin\'92.\'94 Joad said, \'93What\'92s the idear of kickin\'92 the folks o?\'94 \'93Oh! They talked pretty about it. You know what kinda years we been havin\'92. Dust comin\'92 up