 is it? I\'92ll go an\'92 I\'92ll nut the fella.\'92\'91It\'92s the Shawnee Lan\'92 an\'92 Cattle Company. I jus\'92 got orders.\'92 \'91Who\'92s the Shawnee Lan\'92 an\'92 Cattle Company?\'92\'91It ain\'92t nobody. It\'92s a company.\'92 Got a fella crazy. There wasn\'92t nobody you could lay for. Lot a the folks jus\'92 got tired out lookin\'92 for somepin to be mad at\'97but not me. I\'92m mad at all of it. I\'92m stayin\'92.\'94 A large red drop of sun lingered on the horizon and then dripped over and was gone, and the sky was brilliant over the spot where it had gone, and a torn cloud, like a bloody rag, hung over the spot of its going. And dusk crept over the sky from the eastern horizon, and darkness crept over the land from the east. The evening star ashed and glittered in the dusk. The gray cat sneaked away toward the open barn shed and passed inside like a shadow. Joad said, \'93Well, we ain\'92t gonna walk no eight miles to Uncle John\'92s place tonight. My dogs is burned up. How\'92s it if we go to your place, Muley? That\'92s on\'92y about a mile.\'94 \'93Won\'92t do no good.\'94 Muley seemed embarrassed. \'93My wife an\'92 the kids an\'92 her brother all took an\'92 went to California. They wasn\'92t nothin\'92 to eat. They wasn\'92t as mad as me, so they went. They wasn\'92t nothin\'92 to eat here.\'94 The preacher stirred nervously. \'93You should of went too. You shouldn\'92t of broke up the fambly.\'94 \'93I couldn\'92,\'94 said Muley Graves. \'93Somepin jus\'92 wouldn\'92 let me.\'94 \'93Well, by God, I\'92m hungry,\'94 said Joad. \'93Four solemn years I been eatin\'92 right on the minute. My guts is yellin\'92 bloody murder. What you gonna eat, Muley? How you been gettin\'92 your dinner?\'94 Muley said ashamedly, \'93For a while I et frogs an\'92 squirrels an\'92 prairie dogs sometimes. Had to do it. But now I got some wire nooses on the tracks in the dry stream brush. Get rabbits, an\'92 sometimes a prairie chicken. Skunks get caught, an\'92 coons, too.\'94 He reached down, picked up his sack, and emptied it on the porch. Two cottontails and a jackrabbit fell out and rolled over limply, soft and furry. \'93God Awmighty,\'94 said Joad, \'93it\'92s more\'92n four years sence I\'92ve et fresh-killed meat.\'94 Casy picked up one of the cottontails and held it in his hand. \'93You sharin\'92 with us, Muley Graves?\'94 he asked. Muley dgeted in embarrassment. \'93I ain\'92t got no choice in the matter.\'94 He stopped on the ungracious sound of his words. \'93That ain\'92t like I mean it. That ain\'92t. I mean\'94\'97he stumbled\'97\'93what I mean, if a fella\'92s got somepin to eat an\'92 another fella\'92s hungry\'97 why, the rst fella ain\'92t got no choice. I mean, s\'92pose I pick up my rabbits an\'92 go o somewheres an\'92 eat \'92em. See?\'94 \'93I see,\'94 said Casy. \'93I can see that. Muley sees somepin there, Tom. Muley\'92s got a-holt of somepin, an\'92 it\'92s too big for him, an\'92 it\'92s too big for me.\'94 Young Tom rubbed his hands together. \'93Who got a knife? Le\'92s get at these here miserable rodents. Le\'92s get at \'92em.\'94 Muley reached in his pants pocket and produced a large hornhandled pocket knife. Tom Joad took it from him, opened a blade, and smelled it. He drove the blade again and again into the ground and smelled it again, wiped it on his trouser leg, and felt the edge with his thumb. Muley took a quart bottle of water out of his hip pocket and set it on the porch. \'93Go easy on that there water,\'94 he said. \'93That\'92s all there is. This here well\'92s lled in.\'94 Tom took up a rabbit in his hand. \'93One of you go get some bale wire outa the barn. We\'92ll make a re with some a this broken plank from the house.\'94 He looked at the dead rabbit. \'93There ain\'92t nothin\'92 so easy to get ready as a rabbit,\'94 he said. He lifted the skin of the back, slit it, put his ngers in the hole, and tore the skin o. It slipped o like a stocking, slipped o the body to the neck, and o the legs to the paws. Joad picked up the knife again and cut o head and feet. He laid the skin down, slit the rabbit along the ribs, shook out the intestines onto the skin, and then threw the mess o into the cotton eld. And the clean-muscled little body was ready. Joad cut o the legs and cut the meaty back into two pieces. He was picking up the second rabbit when Casy came back with a snarl of bale wire in his hand. \'93Now build up a re and put some stakes up,\'94 said Joad. \'93Jesus Christ, I\'92m hungry for these here creatures!\'94 He cleaned and cut up the rest of the rabbits and strung them on the wire. Muley and Casy tore splintered boards from the wrecked house-corner and started a re, and they drove a stake into the ground on each side to hold the wire. Muley came back to Joad. \'93Look out for boils on that jackrabbit,\'94 he said. \'93I don\'92t like to eat no jackrabbit with boils.\'94 He took a little cloth bag from his pocket and put it on the porch. Joad said, \'93The jack was clean as a whistle\'97Jesus God, you got salt too? By any chance you got some plates an\'92 a tent in your pocket?\'94 He poured salt in his hand and sprinkled it over the pieces of rabbit strung on the wire. The re leaped and threw shadows on the house, and the dry wood crackled and snapped. The sky was almost dark now and the stars were out sharply. The gray cat came out of the barn shed and trotted miaowing toward the re, but, nearly there, it turned and went directly to one of the little piles of rabbit entrails on the ground. It chewed and swallowed, and the entrails hung from its mouth. Casy sat on the ground beside the re, feeding it broken pieces of board, pushing the long boards in as the ame ate o their ends. The evening bats ashed into the relight and out again. The cat crouched back and licked its lips and washed its face and whiskers. Joad held up his rabbit-laden wire between his two hands and walked to the re. \'93Here, take one end, Muley. Wrap your end around that stake. That\'92s good, now! Let\'92s tighten her up. We ought to wait till the re\'92s burned down, but I can\'92t wait.\'94 He made the wire taut, then found a stick and slipped the pieces of meat along the wire until they were over the re. And the ames licked up around the meat and hardened and glazed the surfaces. Joad sat down by the re, but with his stick he moved and turned the rabbit so that it would not become sealed to the wire. \'93This here is a party,\'94 he said. \'93Salt, Muley\'92s got, an\'92 water an\'92 rabbits. I wish he got a pot of hominy in his pocket. That\'92s all I wish.\'94 Muley said over the re, \'93You fellas\'92d think I\'92m touched, the way I live.\'94 \'93Touched, nothin\'92,\'94 said Joad. \'93If you\'92re touched, I wisht ever\'92body was touched.\'94 Muley continued, \'93Well, sir, it\'92s a funny thing. Somepin went an\'92 happened to me when they tol\'92 me I had to get o the place. Fust I was gonna go in an\'92 kill a whole ock a people. Then all my folks all went away out west. An\'92 I got wanderin\'92 aroun\'92. Jus\'92 walkin\'92 aroun\'92. Never went far. Slep\'92 where I was. I was gonna sleep here tonight. That\'92s why I come. I\'92d tell myself, \'91I\'92m lookin\'92 after things so when all the folks come back it\'92ll be all right.\'92 But I knowed that wan\'92t true. There ain\'92t nothin\'92 to look after. The folks ain\'92t never comin\'92 back. I\'92m jus\'92 wanderin\'92 aroun\'92 like a damn ol\'92 graveyard ghos\'92.\'94 \'93Fella gets use\'92 to a place, it\'92s hard to go,\'94 said Casy. \'93Fella gets use\'92 to a way a thinkin\'92, it\'92s hard to leave. I ain\'92t a preacher no more, but all the time I nd I\'92m prayin\'92, not even thinkin\'92 what I\'92m doin\'92.\'94 Joad turned the pieces of meat over on the wire. The juice was dripping now, and every drop, as it fell in the re, shot up a spurt of ame. The smooth surface of the meat was crinkling up and turning a faint brown. \'93Smell her,\'94 said Joad. \'93Jesus, look down an\'92 jus\'92 smell her!\'94 Muley went on, \'93Like a damn ol\'92 graveyard ghos\'92. I been goin\'92 aroun\'92 the places where stu happened. Like there\'92s a place over by our forty; in a gully they\'92s a bush. Fust time I ever laid with a girl was there. Me fourteen an\'92 stampin\'92 an\'92 jerkin\'92 an\'92 snortin\'92 like a buck deer, randy as a billygoat. So I went there an\'92 I laid down on the groun\'92, an\'92 I seen it all happen again. An\'92 there\'92s the place down by the barn where Pa got gored to death by a bull. An\'92 his blood is right in that groun\'92, right now. Mus\'92 be. Nobody never washed it out. An\'92 I put my han\'92 on that groun\'92 where my own pa\'92s blood is part of it.\'94 He paused uneasily. \'93You fellas think I\'92m touched?\'94 Joad turned the meat, and his eyes were inward. Casy, feet drawn up, stared into the re. Fifteen feet back from the men the fed cat was sitting, the long gray tail wrapped neatly around the front feet. A big owl shrieked as it went overhead, and the relight showed its white underside and the spread of its wings. \'93No,\'94 said Casy. \'93You\'92re lonely\'97but you ain\'92t touched.\'94 Muley\'92s tight little face was rigid. \'93I put my han\'92 right on the groun\'92 where that blood is still. An\'92 I seen my pa with a hole through his ches\'92, an\'92 I felt him shiver up against me like he done, an\'92 I seen him kind of settle back an\'92 reach with his han\'92s an\'92 his feet. An\'92 I seen his eyes all milky with hurt, an\'92 then he was still an\'92 his eyes so clear\'97lookin\'92 up. An\'92 me a little kid settin\'92 there, not cryin\'92 nor nothin\'92, jus\'92 settin\'92 there.\'94 He shook his head sharply. Joad turned the meat over and over. \'93An\'92 I went in the room where Joe was born. Bed wasn\'92t there, but it was the room. An\'92 all them things is true, an\'92 they\'92re right in the place they happened. Joe come to life right there. He give a big ol\'92 gasp an\'92 then he let out a squawk you could hear a mile, an\'92 his granma standin\'92 there says, \'91That\'92s a daisy, that\'92s a daisy,\'92 over an\'92 over. An\'92 her so proud she bust three cups that night.\'94 Joad cleared his throat. \'93Think we better eat her now.\'94 \'93Let her get good an\'92 done, good an\'92 brown, awmost black,\'94 said Muley irritably. \'93I wanta talk. I ain\'92t talked to nobody. If I\'92m touched, I\'92m touched, an\'92 that\'92s the end of it. Like a ol\'92 graveyard ghos\'92 goin\'92 to neighbors\'92 houses in the night. Peters\'92, Jacobs\'92, Rance\'92s, Joad\'92s; an\'92 the houses all dark, standin\'92 like miser\'92ble ratty boxes, but they was good parties an\'92 dancin\'92. An\'92 there was meetin\'92s and shoutin\'92 glory. They was weddin\'92s, all in them houses. An\'92 then I\'92d want to go in town an\'92 kill folks. \'92Cause what\'92d they take when they tractored the folks o the lan\'92? What\'92d they get so their \'91margin a prot\'92 was safe? They got Pa dyin\'92 on the groun\'92, an\'92 Joe yellin\'92 his rst breath, an\'92 me jerkin\'92 like a billy goat under a bush in the night. What\'92d they get? God knows the lan\'92 ain\'92t no good. Nobody been able to make a crop for years. But them sons-a-bitches at their desks, they jus\'92 chopped folks in two for their margin a prot. They jus\'92 cut \'92em in two. Place where folks live is them folks. They ain\'92t whole, out lonely on the road in a piled-up car. They ain\'92t alive no more. Them sons-a-bitches killed \'92em.\'94 And he was silent, his thin lips still moving, his chest still panting. He sat and looked down at his hands in the relight. \'93I\'97I ain\'92t talked to nobody for a long time,\'94 he apologized softly. \'93I been sneakin\'92 aroun\'92 like a ol\'92 graveyard ghos\'92.\'94 Casy pushed the long boards into the re and the ames licked up around them and leaped up toward the meat again. The house cracked loudly as the cooler night air contracted the wood. Casy said quietly, \'93I gotta see them folks that\'92s gone out on the road. I got a feelin\'92 I got to see them. They gonna need help no preachin\'92 can give \'92em. Hope of heaven when their lives ain\'92t lived? Holy Sperit when their own sperit is downcast an\'92 sad? They gonna need help. They got to live before they can aord to die.\'94 Joad cried nervously, \'93Jesus Christ, le\'92s eat this meat \'92fore it\'92s smaller\'92n a cooked mouse! Look at her. Smell her.\'94 He leaped to his feet and slid the pieces of meat along the wire until they were clear of the re. He took Muley\'92s knife and sawed through a piece of meat until it was free of the wire. \'93Here\'92s for the preacher,\'94 he said. \'93I tol\'92 you I ain\'92t no preacher.\'94 \'93Well, here\'92s for the man, then.\'94 He cut o another piece. \'93Here, Muley, if you ain\'92t too goddamn upset to eat. This here\'92s jackrabbit. Tougher\'92n a bull-bitch.\'94 He sat back and clamped his long teeth on the meat and tore out a great bite and chewed it. \'93Jesus Christ! Hear her crunch!\'94 And he tore out another bite ravenously. Muley still sat regarding his meat. \'93Maybe I oughtn\'92 to a-talked like that,\'94 he said. \'93Fella should maybe keep stu like that in his head.\'94 Casy looked over, his mouth full of rabbit. He chewed, and his muscled throat convulsed in swallowing. \'93Yes, you should talk,\'94 he said. \'93Sometimes a sad man can talk the sadness right out through his mouth. Sometimes a killin\'92 man can talk the murder right out of his mouth an\'92 not do no murder. You done right. Don\'92t you kill nobody if you can help it.\'94 And he bit out another hunk of rabbit. Joad tossed the bones in the re and jumped up and cut more o the wire. Muley was eating slowly now, and his nervous little eyes went from one to the other of his companions. Joad ate scowling like an animal, and a ring of grease formed around his mouth. For a long time Muley looked at him, almost timidly. He put down the hand that held the meat. \'93Tommy,\'94 he said. Joad looked up and did not stop gnawing the meat. \'93Yeah?\'94 he said, around a mouthful. \'93Tommy, you ain\'92t mad with me talkin\'92 about killin\'92 people? You ain\'92t huy, Tom?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Tom. \'93I ain\'92t huy. It\'92s jus\'92 somepin that happened.\'94 \'93Ever\'92body knowed it was no fault of yours,\'94 said Muley. \'93Ol\'92 man Turnbull said he was gonna get you when ya come out. Says nobody can kill one a his boys. All the folks hereabouts talked him outa it, though.\'94 \'93We was drunk,\'94 Joad said softly. \'93Drunk at a dance. I don\'92 know how she started. An\'92 then I felt that knife go in me, an\'92 that sobered me up. Fust thing I see is Herb comin\'92 for me again with his knife. They was this here shovel leanin\'92 against the schoolhouse, so I grabbed it an\'92 smacked \'92im over the head. I never had nothing against Herb. He was a nice fella. Come a-bullin\'92 after my sister Rosasharn when he was a little fella. No, I liked Herb.\'94 \'93Well, ever\'92body tol\'92 his pa that, an\'92 nally cooled \'92im down. Somebody says they\'92s Hateld blood on his mother\'92s side in ol\'92 Turnbull, an\'92 he\'92s got to live up to it. I don\'92t know about that. Him an\'92 his folks went on to California six months ago.\'94 Joad took the last of the rabbit from the wire and passed it around. He settled back and ate more slowly now, chewed evenly, and wiped the grease from his mouth with his sleeve. And his eyes, dark and half closed, brooded as he looked into the dying re. \'93Ever\'92body\'92s goin\'92 west,\'94 he said. \'93I got me a parole to keep. Can\'92t leave the state.\'94 \'93Parole?\'94 Muley asked. \'93I heard about them. How do they work?\'94 \'93Well, I got out early, three years early. They\'92s stu I gotta do, or they send me back in. Got to report ever\'92 so often.\'94 \'93How they treat ya there in McAlester? My woman\'92s cousin was in McAlester an\'92 they give him hell.\'94 \'93It ain\'92t so bad,\'94 said Joad. \'93Like ever\'92place else. They give ya hell if ya raise hell. You get along O.K. les\'92 some guard gets it in for ya. Then you catch plenty hell. I got along O.K. Minded my own business, like any guy would. I learned to write nice as hell. Birds an\'92 stu like that, too; not just word writin\'92. My ol\'92 man\'92ll be sore when he sees me whip out a bird in one stroke. Pa\'92s gonna be mad when he sees me do that. He don\'92t like no fancy stu like that. He don\'92t even like word writin\'92. Kinda scares \'92im, I guess. Ever\'92 time Pa seen writin\'92, somebody took somepin away from \'92im.\'94 \'93They didn\'92 give you no beatin\'92s or nothin\'92 like that?\'94 \'93No, I jus\'92 tended my own aairs. \'92Course you get goddamn good an\'92 sick a-doin\'92 the same thing day after day for four years. If you done somepin you was ashamed of, you might think about that. But, hell, if I seen Herb Turnbull comin\'92 for me with a knife right now, I\'92d squash him down with a shovel again.\'94 \'93Anybody would,\'94 said Muley. The preacher stared into the re, and his high forehead was white in the settling dark. The ash of little ames picked out the cords of his neck. His hands, clasped about his knees, were busy pulling knuckles. Joad threw the last bones into the re and licked his ngers and then wiped them on his pants. He stood up and brought the bottle of water from the porch, took a sparing drink, and passed the bottle before he sat down again. He went on, \'93The thing that give me the mos\'92 trouble was, it didn\'92 make no sense. You don\'92t look for no sense when lightnin\'92 kills a cow, or it comes up a ood. That\'92s jus\'92 the way things is. But when a bunch of men take an\'92 lock you up four years, it ought to have some meaning. Men is supposed to think things out. Here they put me in, an\'92 keep me an\'92 feed me four years. That ought