 He was silent. His words lay in the group, and the group was silent. \'93He\'92s a nice fella,\'94 Tom added. \'93We\'92ve knowed him a long time. Talks a little wild sometimes, but he talks sensible.\'94 And he relinquished the proposal to the family. The light was going gradually. Ma left the group and went into the house, and the iron clang of the stove came from the house. In a moment she walked back to the brooding council. Grampa said, \'93They was two ways a thinkin\'92. Some folks use\'92 ta gger that a preacher was poison luck.\'94 Tom said, \'93This fella says he ain\'92t a preacher no more.\'94 Grampa waved his hand back and forth. \'93Once a fella\'92s a preacher, he\'92s always a preacher. That\'92s somepin you can\'92t get shut of. They was some folks ggered it was a good respectable thing to have a preacher along. Ef somebody died, preacher buried \'92em. Weddin\'92 come due, or overdue, an\'92 there\'92s your preacher. Baby come, an\'92 you got a christener right under the roof. Me, I always said they was preachers an\'92 preachers. Got to pick \'92em. I kinda like this fella. He ain\'92t sti.\'94 Pa dug his stick into the dust and rolled it between his ngers so that it bored a little hole. \'93They\'92s more to this than is he lucky, or is he a nice fella,\'94 Pa said. \'93We got to gger close. It\'92s a sad thing to gger close. Le\'92s see, now. There\'92s Grampa an\'92 Granma\'97that\'92s two. An\'92 me an\'92 John an\'92 Ma\'97that\'92s ve. An\'92 Noah an\'92 Tommy an\'92 Al\'97 that\'92s eight. Rosasharn an\'92 Connie is ten, an\'92 Ruthie an\'92 Winel\'92 is twelve. We got to take the dogs \'92cause what\'92ll we do else? Can\'92t shoot a good dog, an\'92 there ain\'92t nobody to give \'92em to. An\'92 that\'92s fourteen.\'94 \'93Not countin\'92 what chickens is left, an\'92 two pigs,\'94 said Noah. Pa said, \'93I aim to get those pigs salted down to eat on the way. We gonna need meat. Carry the salt kegs right with us. But I\'92m wonderin\'92