 \'93We go in like the law says an\'92 they\'92ll come out for him. We on\'92y got a hundred an\'92 fty dollars. They take forty to bury Grampa an\'92 we won\'92t get to California\'97or else they\'92ll bury him a pauper.\'94 The men stirred restively, and they studied the darkening ground in front of their knees. Pa said softly, \'93Grampa buried his pa with his own hand, done it in dignity, an\'92 shaped the grave nice with his own shovel. That was a time when a man had the right to be buried by his own son an\'92 a son had the right to bury his own father.\'94 \'93The law says dierent now,\'94 said Uncle John. \'93Sometimes the law can\'92t be foller\'92d no way,\'94 said Pa. \'93Not in decency, anyways. They\'92s lots a times you can\'92t. When Floyd was loose an\'92 goin\'92 wild, law said we got to give him up\'97an\'92 nobody give him up. Sometimes a fella got to sift the law. I\'92m sayin\'92 now I got the right to bury my own pa. Anybody got somepin to say?\'94 The preacher rose high on his elbow. \'93Law changes,\'94 he said, \'93but \'91got to\'92s\'92 go on. You got the right to do what you got to do.\'94 Pa turned to Uncle John. \'93It\'92s your right too, John. You got any word against?\'94 \'93No word against,\'94 said Uncle John. \'93On\'92y it\'92s like hidin\'92 him in the night. Grampa\'92s way was t\'92come out a-shootin\'92.\'94 Pa said ashamedly, \'93We can\'92t do like Grampa done. We got to get to California \'92fore our money gives out.\'94 Tom broke in, \'93Sometimes fellas workin\'92 dig up a man an\'92 then they raise hell an\'92 gger he been killed. The gov\'92ment\'92s got more interest in a dead man than a live one. They\'92ll go hell-scrapin\'92 tryin\'92 to n\'92 out who he was and how he died. I oer we put a note of writin\'92 in a bottle an\'92 lay it with Grampa, tellin\'92 who he is an\'92 how he died, an\'92 why he\'92s buried here.\'94 Pa nodded agreement. \'93Tha\'92s good. Wrote out in a nice han\'92 Be not so lonesome too, knowin\'92 his name is there with \'92im, not jus\'92 a old fella lonesome underground. Any more stu to say?\'94 The circle was silent. Pa turned his head to Ma. \'93You\'92ll lay \'92im out?\'94 \'93I\'92ll lay \'92im out,\'94 said Ma. \'93But who\'92s to get supper?\'94 Sairy Wilson said, \'93I\'92ll get supper. You go right ahead. Me an\'92 that big girl of yourn.\'94 \'93We sure thank you,\'94 said Ma. \'93Noah, you get into them kegs an\'92 bring out some nice pork. Salt won\'92t be deep in it yet, but it\'92ll be right nice eatin\'92.\'94 \'93We got a half sack a potatoes,\'94 said Sairy. Ma said, \'93Gimme two half-dollars.\'94 Pa dug in his pocket and gave her the silver. She found the basin, lled it full of water, and went into the tent. It was nearly dark in there. Sairy came in and lighted a candle and stuck it upright on a box and then she went out. For a moment Ma looked down at the dead old man. And then in pity she tore a strip from her own apron and tied up his jaw. She straightened his limbs, folded his hands over his chest. She held his eyelids down and laid a silver piece on each one. She buttoned his shirt and washed his face. Sairy looked in, saying, \'93Can I give you any help?\'94 Ma looked slowly up. \'93Come in,\'94 she said. \'93I like to talk to ya.\'94 \'93That\'92s a good big girl you got,\'94 said Sairy. \'93She\'92s right in peelin\'92 potatoes. What can I do to help?\'94 \'93I was gonna wash Grampa all over,\'94 said Ma, \'93but he got no other clo\'92es to put on. An\'92 \'92course your quilt\'92s spoilt. Can\'92t never get the smell a death from a quilt. I seen a dog growl an\'92 shake at a mattress my ma died on, an\'92 that was two years later. We\'92ll wrop \'92im in your quilt. We\'92ll make it up to you. We got a quilt for you.\'94 Sairy said, \'93You shouldn\'92 talk like that. We\'92re proud to help. I ain\'92t felt so\'97safe in a long time. People needs\'97to help.\'94 Ma nodded. \'93They do,\'94 she said. She looked long into the old whiskery face, with its bound jaw and silver eyes shining in the candlelight. \'93He ain\'92t gonna look natural. We\'92ll wrop him up.\'94 \'93The ol\'92 lady took it good.\'94 \'93Why, she\'92s so old,\'94 said Ma, \'93maybe she don\'92t even rightly know what happened. Maybe she won\'92t really know for quite a while. Besides, us folks takes a pride holdin\'92 in. My pa used to say, \'91Anybody can break down. It takes a man not to.\'92 We always try to hold in.\'94 She folded the quilt neatly about Grampa\'92s legs and around his shoulders. She brought the corner of the quilt over his head like a cowl and pulled it down over his face. Sairy handed her half-a-dozen big safety pins, and she pinned the quilt neatly and tightly about the long package. And at last she stood up. \'93It won\'92t be a bad burying,\'94 she said. \'93We got a preacher to see him in, an\'92 his folks is all aroun\'92.\'94 Suddenly she swayed a little, and Sairy went to her and steadied her. \'93It\'92s sleep \'97\'94 Ma said in a shamed tone. \'93No, I\'92m awright. We been so busy gettin\'92 ready, you see.\'94 \'93Come out in the air,\'94 Sairy said. \'93Yeah, I\'92m all done here.\'94 Sairy blew out the candle and the two went out. A bright re burned in the bottom of the little gulch. And Tom, with sticks and wire, had made supports from which two kettles hung and bubbled furiously, and good steam poured out under the lids. Rose of Sharon knelt on the ground out of range of the burning heat, and she had a long spoon in her hand. She saw Ma come out of the tent, and she stood up and went to her. \'93Ma,\'94 she said. \'93I got to ask.\'94 \'93Scared again?\'94 Ma asked. \'93Why, you can\'92t get through nine months without sorrow.\'94 \'93But will it\'97hurt the baby?\'94 Ma said, \'93They used to be a sayin\'92, \'91A chile born outa sorrow\'92ll be a happy chile.\'92 Isn\'92t that so, Mis\'92 Wilson?\'94 \'93I heard it like that,\'94 said Sairy. \'93An\'92 I heard the other: