\'93How \'92bout \'91God have mercy on his soul\'92?\'94 \'93No,\'94 said Tom. \'93Sounds too much like he was hung. I\'92ll copy somepin.\'94 He turned the pages and read, mumbling his lips, saying the words under his breath. \'93Here\'92s a good short one,\'94 he said. \'93\'91An\'92 Lot said unto them, Oh, not so, my Lord.\'94\'92 \'93Don\'92t mean nothin\'92,\'94 said Ma. \'93Long\'92s you\'92re gonna put one down, it might\'92s well mean somepin.\'94 Sairy said, \'93Turn to Psalms, over further. You kin always get somepin outa Psalms.\'94 Tom ipped the pages and looked down the verses. \'93Now here is one,\'94 he said. \'93This here\'92s a nice one, just blowed full a religion: \'91Blessed is he whose transgression is forgiven, whose sin is covered.\'92 How\'92s that?\'94 \'93That\'92s real nice,\'94 said Ma. \'93Put that one in.\'94 Tom wrote it carefully. Ma rinsed and wiped a fruit jar and Tom screwed the lid down tight on it. \'93Maybe the preacher ought to wrote it,\'94 he said. Ma said, \'93No, the preacher wan\'92t no kin.\'94 She took the jar from him and went into the dark tent. She unpinned the covering and slipped the fruit jar in under the thin cold hands and pinned the comforter tight again. And then she went back to the re. The men came from the grave, their faces shining with perspiration. \'93Awright,\'94 said Pa. He and John and Noah and Al went into the tent, and they came out carrying the long, pinned bundle between them. They carried it to the grave. Pa leaped into the hole and received the bundle in his arms and laid it gently down. Uncle John put out a hand and helped Pa out of the hole. Pa asked, \'93How about Granma?\'94 \'93I\'92ll see,\'94 Ma said. She walked to the mattress and looked down at the old woman for a moment. Then she went back to the grave. \'93Sleepin\'92,\'94 she said. \'93Maybe she\'92d hold it against me, but I ain\'92t agonna wake her up. She\'92s tar\'92d.\'94 Pa said, \'93Where at\'92s the preacher? We oughta have a