ad. Pa said, \'93Amen,\'94 and the others muttered, \'93A-men.\'94 Then Pa took the shovel, half lled it with dirt, and spread it gently into the black hole. He handed the shovel to Uncle John, and John dropped in a shovelful. Then the shovel went from hand to hand until every man had his turn. When all had taken their duty and their right, Pa attacked the mound of loose dirt and hurriedly lled the hole. The women moved back to the re to see to supper. Ruthie and Wineld watched, absorbed. Ruthie said solemnly, \'93Grampa\'92s down under there.\'94 And Wineld looked at her with horried eyes. And then he ran away to the re and sat on the ground and sobbed to himself. Pa half lled the hole, and then he stood panting with the eort while Uncle John nished it. And John was shaping up the mound when Tom stopped him. \'93Listen,\'94 Tom said. \'93\'92F we leave a grave, they\'92ll have it open in no time. We got to hide it. Level her o an\'92 we\'92ll strew dry grass. We got to do that.\'94 Pa said, \'93I didn\'92 think a that. It ain\'92t right to leave a grave unmounded.\'94 \'93Can\'92t he\'92p it,\'94 said Tom. \'93They\'92d dig \'92im right up, an\'92 we\'92d get it for breakin\'92 the law. You know what I get if I break the law.\'94 \'93Yeah,\'94 Pa said. \'93I forgot that.\'94 He took the shovel from John and leveled the grave. \'93She\'92ll sink, come winter,\'94 he said. \'93Can\'92t he\'92p that,\'94 said Tom. \'93We\'92ll be a long ways o by winter. Tromp her in good, an\'92 we\'92ll strew stu over her.\'94 When the pork and potatoes were done the families sat about on the ground and ate, and they were quiet, staring into the re. Wilson, tearing a slab of meat with his teeth, sighed with contentment. \'93Nice eatin\'92 pig,\'94 he said. \'93Well,\'94 Pa explained, \'93we had a couple shoats, an\'92 we thought we might\'92s well eat \'92em. Can\'92t get nothin\'92 for them. When we get kinda use\'92 ta movin\'92 an\'92 Ma can set up bread, why, it\'92ll be pretty nice, seein\'92 the country an\'92 two kags a\'92 pork right in the truck. How long you folks been on the road?\'94 Wilson cleared his teeth with his tongue and swallowed. \'93We ain\'92t been lucky,\'94 he said. \'93We been three weeks from home.\'94 \'93Why, God Awmighty, we aim to be in California in ten days or less.\'94 Al broke in, \'93I dunno, Pa. With that load we\'92re packin\'92, we maybe ain\'92t never gonna get there. Not if they\'92s mountains to go over.\'94 They were silent about the re. Their faces were turned downward and their hair and foreheads showed in the relight. Above the little dome of the relight the summer stars shone thinly, and the heat of the day was gradually withdrawing. On her mattress, away from the re, Granma whimpered softly like a puppy. The heads of all turned in her direction. Ma said, \'93Rosasharn, like a good girl go lay down with Granma. She needs somebody now. She\'92s knowin\'92, now.\'94 Rose of Sharon got to her feet and walked to the mattress and lay beside the old woman, and the murmur of their soft voices drifted to the re. Rose of Sharon and Granma whispered together on the mattress. Noah said, \'93Funny thing is\'97losin\'92 Grampa ain\'92t made me feel no dierent than I done before. I ain\'92t no sadder than I was.\'94 \'93It\'92s just the same thing,\'94 Casy said. \'93Grampa an\'92 the old place, they was jus\'92 the same thing.\'94 Al said, \'93It\'92s a goddamn shame. He been talkin\'92 what he\'92s gonna do, how he gonna squeeze grapes over his head an\'92 let the juice run in his whiskers, an\'92 all stu like that.\'94 Casy said, \'93He was foolin\'92, all the time. I think he knowed it. An\'92 Grampa didn\'92 die tonight. He died the minute you took \'92im o the place.\'94 \'93You sure a that?\'94 Pa cried. \'93Why, no. Oh, he was breathin\'92,\'94 Casy went on, \'93but he was dead. He was that place, an\'92 he knowed it.\'94 Uncle John said, \'93Did you know he was a-dyin\'92?\'94 \'93Yeah,\'94 said Casy. 