ehind. It was dark inside. He felt his way to the mattress on the oor, and he stretched out and cried in his bed, and the cars whizzing by on the highway only strengthened the walls of his loneliness. Tom said, \'93If you\'92d tol\'92 me we\'92d get this here thing an\'92 get her in tonight, I\'92d said you was nuts.\'94 \'93We\'92ll get her in awright,\'94 said Al. \'93You got to do her, though. I\'92d be scared I\'92d get her too tight an\'92 she\'92d burn out, or too loose an\'92 she\'92d hammer out.\'94 \'93I\'92ll stick her in,\'94 said Tom. \'93If she goes out again, she goes out. I got nothin\'92 to lose.\'94 Al peered into the dusk. The lights made no impression on the gloom; but ahead, the eyes of a hunting cat ashed green in reection of the lights. \'93You sure give that fella hell,\'94 Al said. \'93Sure did tell him where to lay down his dogs.\'94 \'93Well, goddamn it, he was askin\'92 for it! Jus\'92 a pattin\'92 his-self \'92cause he got one eye, puttin\'92 all the blame on his eye. He\'92s a lazy, dirty son-of-a-bitch. Maybe he can snap out of it if he knowed people was wise to him.\'94 Al said, \'93Tom, it wasn\'92t nothin\'92 I done burned out that bearin\'92.\'94 Tom was silent for a moment, then, \'93I\'92m gonna take a fall outa you, Al. You jus\'92 scrabblin\'92 ass over tit, fear somebody gonna pin some blame on you. I know what\'92s a matter. Young fella, all full a piss an\'92 vinegar. Wanta be a hell of a guy all the time. But, goddamn it, Al, don\'92 keep ya guard up when nobody ain\'92t sparrin\'92 with ya. You gonna be all right.\'94 Al did not answer him. He looked straight ahead. The truck rattled and banged over the road. A cat whipped out from the side of the road and Al swerved to hit it, but the wheels missed and the cat leaped into the grass. \'93Nearly got him,\'94 said Al. \'93Say, Tom. You heard Connie talkin\'92 how he\'92s gonna study nights? I been thinkin\'92 maybe I\'92d study nights too. You know, radio or television or Diesel engines. Fella might get started that-a-way.\'94 \'93Might,\'94 said Tom. \'93Find out how much they gonna sock ya for the lessons, rst. An\'92gger out if you\'92re gonna study \'92em. There was fellas takin\'92 them mail lessons in McAlester. I never knowed one of \'92em that nished up. Got sick of it an\'92 left \'92em slide.\'94 \'93God Awmighty, we forgot to get somepin to eat.\'94 \'93Well, Ma sent down plenty; preacher couldn\'92 eat it all. Be some lef\'92. I wonder how long it\'92ll take us to get to California.\'94 \'93Christ, I don\'92 know. Jus\'92 plug away at her.\'94 They fell into silence, and the dark came and the stars were sharp and white. Casy got out of the back seat of the Dodge and strolled to the side of the road when the truck pulled up. \'93I never expected you so soon,\'94 he said. Tom gathered the parts in the piece of sacking on the oor. \'93We was lucky,\'94 he said. \'93Got a ashlight, too. Gonna x her right up.\'94 \'93You forgot to take your dinner,\'94 said Casy. \'93I\'92ll get it when I nish. Here, Al, pull o the road a little more an\'92 come hol\'92 the light for me.\'94 He went directly to the Dodge and crawled under on his back. Al crawled under on his belly and directed the beam of the ashlight. \'93Not in my eyes. There, put her up.\'94 Tom worked the piston up into the cylinder, twisting and turning. The brass wire caught a little on the cylinder wall. With a quick push he forced it past the rings. \'93Lucky she\'92s loose or the compression\'92d stop her. I think she\'92s gonna work all right.\'94 \'93Hope that wire don\'92t clog the rings,\'94 said Al. \'93Well, that\'92s why I hammered her at. She won\'92t roll o. I think she\'92ll jus\'92 melt out an\'92 maybe give the walls a brass plate.\'94 \'93Think she might score the walls?\'94 Tom laughed. \'93Jesus Christ, them walls can take it. She\'92s drinkin\'92 oil like a gopher hole awready. Little more ain\'92t gonna hurt none.\'94 He worked the rod down over the shaft and tested the lower half. \'93She\'92ll take some shim.\'94 He said, \'93Casy!\'94 \'93Yeah.\'94 \'93I\'92m takin\'92 up this here bearing now. Get out to that crank an\'92 turn her over slow when I tell ya.\'94 He tightened the bolts. \'93Now. Over slow!\'94 And as the angular shaft turned, he worked the bearing against it. \'93Too much shim,\'94 Tom said. \'93Hold it, Casy.\'94 He took out the bolts and removed thin shims from each side and put the bolts back. \'93Try her again, Casy!\'94 And he worked the rod again. \'93She\'92s a lit-tle bit loose yet. Wonder if she\'92d be too tight if I took out more shim. I\'92ll try her.\'94 Again he removed the bolts and took out another pair of the thin strips. \'93Now try her, Casy.\'94 \'93That looks good,\'94 said Al. Tom called, \'93She any harder to turn, Casy?\'94 \'93No, I don\'92t think so.\'94 \'93Well, I think she\'92s snug here. I hope to God she is. Can\'92t hone no babbitt without tools. This here socket wrench makes her a hell of a lot easier.\'94 Al said, \'93Boss a that yard gonna be purty mad when he looks for that size socket an\'92 she ain\'92t there.\'94 \'93That\'92s his screwin\'92,\'94 said Tom. \'93We didn\'92 steal her.\'94 He tapped the cotter-pins in and bent the ends out. \'93I think that\'92s good. Look, Casy, you hold the light while me an\'92 Al get this here pan up.\'94 Casy knelt down and took the ashlight. He kept the beam on the working hands as they patted the gasket gently in place and lined the holes with the pan bolts. The two men strained at the weight of the pan, caught the end bolts, and then set in the others; and when they were all engaged, Tom took them up little by little until the pan settled evenly in against the gasket, and he tightened hard against the nuts. \'93I guess that\'92s her,\'94 Tom said. He tightened the oil tap, looked carefully up at the pan, and took the light and searched the ground. \'93There she is. Le\'92s get the oil back in her.\'94 They crawled out and poured the bucket of oil back in the crank case. Tom inspected the gasket for leaks. \'93O.K., Al. Turn her over,\'94 he said. Al got into the car and stepped on the starter. The motor caught with a roar. Blue smoke poured from the exhaust pipe. \'93Throttle down!\'94 Tom shouted. \'93She\'92ll burn oil till that wire goes. Gettin\'92 thinner now.\'94 And as the motor turned over, he listened carefully. \'93Put up the spark an\'92 let her idle.\'94 He listened again. \'93O.K., Al. Turn her o. I think we done her. Where\'92s that meat now?\'94 \'93You make a darn good mechanic,\'94 Al said. \'93Why not? I worked in the shop a year. We\'92ll take her good an\'92 slow for a couple hunderd miles. Give her a chance to work in.\'94 They wiped their grease-covered hands on bunches of weeds and nally rubbed them on their trousers. They fell hungrily on the boiled pork and swigged the water from the bottle. \'93I like to starved,\'94 said Al. \'93What we gonna do now, go on to the camp?\'94 \'93I dunno,\'94 said Tom. \'93Maybe they\'92d charge us a extry half-buck. Le\'92s go on an\'92 talk to the folks\'97tell \'92em we\'92re xed. Then if they wanta sock us extry\'97we\'92ll move on. The folks\'92ll wanta know. Jesus, I\'92m glad Ma stopped us this afternoon. Look around with the light, Al. See we don\'92t leave nothin\'92. Get that socket wrench in. We may need her again.\'94 Al searched the ground with the ashlight. \'93Don\'92t see nothin\'92.\'94 \'93All right. I\'92ll drive her. You bring the truck, Al.\'94 Tom started the engine. The preacher got in the car. Tom moved slowly, keeping the engine at a low speed, and Al followed in the truck. He crossed the shallow ditch, crawling in low gear. Tom said, \'93These here Dodges can pull a house in low gear. She\'92s sure ratio\'92d down. Good thing for us\'97I wanta break that bearin\'92 in easy.\'94 On the highway the Dodge moved along slowly. The 12-volt headlights threw a short blob of yellowish light on the pavement. Casy turned to Tom. \'93Funny how you fellas can x a car. Jus\'92 light right in an\'92 x her. I couldn\'92t x no car, not even now when I seen you do it.\'94 \'93Got to grow into her when you\'92re a little kid,\'94 Tom said. \'93It ain\'92t jus\'92 knowin\'92. It\'92s more\'92n that. Kids now can tear down a car \'92thout even thinkin\'92 about it.\'94 A jackrabbit got caught in the lights and he bounced along ahead, cruising easily, his great ears opping with every jump. Now and then he tried to break o the road, but the wall of darkness thrust him back. Far ahead bright headlights appeared and bore down on them. The rabbit hesitated, faltered, then turned and bolted toward the lesser lights of the Dodge. There was a small soft jolt as he went under the wheels. The oncoming car swished by. \'93We sure squashed him,\'94 said Casy. Tom said, \'93Some fellas like to hit \'92em. Gives me a little shakes ever\'92 time. Car sounds OK. Them rings must a broke loose by now. She ain\'92t smokin\'92 so bad.\'94 \'93You done a nice job,\'94 said Casy. A small wooden house dominated the camp ground, and on the porch of the house a gasoline lantern hissed and threw its white glare in a great circle. Half a dozen tents were pitched near the house, and cars stood beside the tents. Cooking for the night was over, but the coals of the campres still glowed on the ground by the camping places. A group of men had gathered to the porch where the lantern burned, and their faces were strong and muscled under the harsh white light, light that threw black shadows of their hats over their foreheads and eyes and made their chins seem to jut out. They sat on the steps, and some stood on the ground, resting their elbows on the porch oor. The proprietor, a sullen lanky man, sat in a chair on the porch. He leaned back against the wall, and he drummed his ngers on his knee. Inside the house a kerosene lamp burned, but its thin light was blasted by the hissing glare of the gasoline lantern. The