ors, I can see why they was mad.\'94 Thomas said, \'93I watched it a long time. There\'92s always red agitators just before a pay cut. Always. Goddamn it, they got me trapped. Now, what are you going to do? Twenty-ve cents?\'94 Timothy looked at the ground. \'93I\'92ll work,\'94 he said. \'93Me too,\'94 said Wilkie. Tom said, \'93Seems like I walked into somepin. Sure, I\'92ll work. I got to work.\'94 Thomas pulled a bandanna out of his hip pocket and wiped his mouth and chin. \'93I don\'92t know how long it can go on. I don\'92t know how you men can feed a family on what you get now.\'94 \'93We can while we work,\'94 Wilkie said. \'93It\'92s when we don\'92t git work.\'94 Thomas looked at his watch. \'93Well, let\'92s go out and dig some ditch. By God,\'94 he said, \'93I\'92m a-gonna tell you. You fellas live in that government camp, don\'92t you?\'94 Timothy stiened. \'93Yes, sir.\'94 \'93And you have dances every Saturday night?\'94 Wilkie smiled. \'93We sure do.\'94 \'93Well, look out next Saturday night.\'94 Suddenly Timothy straightened. He stepped close. \'93What you mean? I belong to the Central Committee. I got to know.\'94 Thomas looked apprehensive. \'93Don\'92t you ever tell I told.\'94 \'93What is it?\'94 Timothy demanded. \'93Well, the Association don\'92t like the government camps. Can\'92t get a deputy in there. The people make their own laws, I hear, and you can\'92t arrest a man without a warrant. Now if there was a big ght and maybe shooting\'97a bunch of deputies could go in and clean out the camp.\'94 Timothy had changed. His shoulders were straight and his eyes cold. \'93What you mean?\'94 \'93Don\'92t you ever tell where you heard,\'94 Thomas said uneasily. \'93There\'92s going to be a ght in the camp Saturday night. And there\'92s going to be deputies ready to go in.\'94 Tom demanded, \'93Why, for God\'92s sake? Those folks ain\'92t bothering nobody.\'94 \'93I\'92ll tell you why,\'94 Thomas said. \'93Those folks in the camp are getting used t