ed. \'93They\'92s a committee\'97a ladies\'92 committee a-comin\'92 to visit. Git up now, an\'92 git washed. An\'92 while we was a-sleepin\'92 an\'92 a-snorin\'92, Tom\'92s went out an\'92 got work. Git up, now.\'94 They came sleepily out of the tent. Uncle John staggered a little, and his face was pained. \'93Git over to that house and wash up,\'94 Ma ordered. \'93We got to get breakfus\'92 an\'92 be ready for the Committee.\'94 She went to a little pile of split wood in the camp lot. She started a re and put up her cooking irons. \'93Pone,\'94 she said to herself. \'93Pone an\'92 gravy. That\'92s quick. Got to be quick.\'94 She talked on to herself, and Ruthie and Wineld stood by, wondering. The smoke of the morning res arose all over the camp, and the mutter of talk came from all sides. Rose of Sharon, unkempt and sleepy-eyed, crawled out of the tent. Ma turned from the cornmeal she was measuring in stfuls. She looked at the girl\'92s wrinkled dirty dress, at her frizzled uncombed hair. \'93You got to clean up,\'94 she said briskly. \'93Go right over and clean up. You got a clean dress. I washed it. Git your hair combed. Git the seeds out a your eyes.\'94 Ma was excited. Rose of Sharon said sullenly, \'93I don\'92 feel good. I wisht Connie would come. I don\'92t feel like doin\'92 nothin\'92 \'92thout Connie.\'94 Ma turned full around on her. The yellow cornmeal clung to her hands and wrists. \'93Rosasharn,\'94 she said sternly, \'93you git upright. You jus\'92 been mopin\'92 enough. They\'92s a ladies\'92 committee a-comin\'92, an\'92 the fambly ain\'92t gonna be frawny when they get here.\'94 \'93But I don\'92 feel good.\'94 Ma advanced on her, mealy hands held out. \'93Git,\'94 Ma said. \'93They\'92s times when how you feel got to be kep\'92 to yourself.\'94 \'93I\'92m a-goin\'92 to vomit,\'94 Rose of Sharon whined. \'93Well, go an\'92 vomit. \'92Course you\'92re gonna vomit. Ever\'92body does. Git it over an\'92 then you clean up, an\'92 you wash your legs an