nd she strode away titanically, and her eyes shone with virtue. Rose of Sharon watched her go, and then she put her head down on her hands and whimpered into her palms. A soft voice sounded beside her. She looked up, ashamed. It was the little white-clad manager. \'93Don\'92t worry,\'94 he said. \'93Don\'92t you worry.\'94 Her eyes blinded with tears. \'93But I done it,\'94 she cried. \'93I hugdanced. I didn\'92 tell her. I done it in Sallisaw. Me an\'92 Connie.\'94 \'93Don\'92t worry,\'94 he said. \'93She says I\'92ll drop the baby.\'94 \'93I know she does. I kind of keep my eye on her. She\'92s a good woman, but she makes people unhappy.\'94 Rose of Sharon snied wetly. \'93She knowed two girls los\'92 their baby right in this here camp.\'94 The manager squatted down in front of her. \'93Look!\'94 he said. \'93Listen to me. I know them too. They were too hungry and too tired. And they worked too hard. And they rode on a truck over bumps. They were sick. It wasn\'92t their fault.\'94 \'93But she said\'97\'97\'94 \'93Don\'92t worry. That woman likes to make trouble.\'94 \'93But she says you was the devil.\'94 \'93I know she does. That\'92s because I won\'92t let her make people miserable.\'94 He patted her shoulder. \'93Don\'92t you worry. She doesn\'92t know.\'94 And he walked quickly away. Rose of Sharon looked after him; his lean shoulders jerked as he walked. She was still watching his slight gure when Ma came back, clean and pink, her hair combed and wet, and gathered in a knot. She wore her gured dress and the old cracked shoes; and the little earrings hung in her ears. \'93I done it,\'94 she said. \'93I stood in there an\'92 let warm water come a- oodin\'92 an\'92 a-owin\'92 down over me. An\'92 they was a lady says you can do it ever\'92 day if you want. An\'92\'97them ladies\'92 committee come yet?\'94 \'93Uh-uh!\'94 said the girl. \'93An\'92 you jus\'92 set there an\'92 didn\'92 redd up the camp none!\'94 Ma gathered up the tin dishes as she spoke. \'93We g