ssie Bullitt said sternly, \'93Annie, I\'92ll thank you to remember I\'92m Chair.\'94 \'93Oh! Sure, sure. But next week I am.\'94 \'93Well, you wait\'92ll next week then. We change ever\'92 week,\'94 she explained to Ma. \'93Sure you wouldn\'92 like a little coee?\'94 Ma asked helplessly. \'93No, thank you.\'94 Jessie took charge. \'93We gonna show you \'92bout the sanitary unit fust, an\'92 then if you wanta, we\'92ll sign you up in the Ladies\'92 Club an\'92 give you duty. \'92Course you don\'92 have to join.\'94 \'93Does\'97does it cost much?\'94 \'93Don\'92t cost nothing but work. An\'92 when you\'92re knowed, maybe you can be \'92lected to this committee,\'94 Annie interrupted. \'93Jessie, here, is on the committee for the whole camp. She\'92s a big committee lady.\'94 Jessie smiled with pride. \'93\'92Lected unanimous,\'94 she said. \'93Well, Mis\'92 Joad, I guess it\'92s time we tol\'92 you \'92bout how the camp runs.\'94 Ma said, \'93This here\'92s my girl, Rosasharn.\'94 \'93How do,\'94 they said. \'93Better come \'92long too.\'94 The huge Jessie spoke, and her manner was full of dignity and kindness, and her speech was rehearsed. \'93You shouldn\'92 think we\'92re a-buttin\'92 into your business, Mis\'92 Joad. This here camp got a lot of stu ever\'92body uses. An\'92 we got rules we made ourself. Now we\'92re a-goin\'92 to the unit. That there, ever\'92body uses, an\'92 ever\'92body got to take care of it.\'94 They strolled to the unroofed section where the wash trays were, twenty of them. Eight were in use, the women bending over, scrubbing the clothes, and the piles of wrung-out clothes were heaped on the clean concrete oor. \'93Now you can use these here any time you want,\'94 Jessie said. \'93The on\'92y thing is, you got to leave \'92em clean.\'94 The women who were washing looked up with interest. Jessie said loudly, \'93This here\'92s Mis\'92 Joad an\'92 Rosasharn, come to live.\'94 They greeted Ma in a chorus, and Ma made a dumpy little bow at them