is usin\'92 too much.\'92 Come right up in meetin\'92!\'94 Ma was following the conversation breathlessly. \'93Stealin\'92 it\'97what for?\'94 \'93Well,\'94 said Jessie, \'93we had trouble before. Las\'92 time they was three little girls cuttin\'92 paper dolls out of it. Well, we caught them. But this time we don\'92t know. Hardly put a roll out \'92fore it\'92s gone. Come right up in meetin\'92. One lady says we oughta have a little bell that rings ever\'92 time the roll turns oncet. Then we could count how many ever\'92body takes.\'94 She shook her head. \'93I jes\'92 don\'92 know,\'94 she said. \'93I been worried all week. Somebody\'92s a-stealin\'92 toilet paper from Unit Four.\'94 From the doorway came a whining voice, \'93Mis\'92 Bullitt.\'94 The committee turned. \'93Mis\'92 Bullitt, I hearn what you says.\'94 A ushed, perspiring woman stood in the doorway. \'93I couldn\'92 git up in meetin\'92. Mis\'92 Bullitt. I jes\'92 couldn\'92. They\'92d a-laughed or somepin.\'94 \'93What you talkin\'92 about?\'94 Jessie advanced. \'93Well, we-all\'97maybe\'97it\'92s us. But we ain\'92t a-stealin\'92, Mis\'92 Bullitt.\'94 Jessie advanced on her, and the perspiration beaded out on the ustery confessor. \'93We can\'92t he\'92p it. Mis\'92 Bullitt.\'94 \'93Now you tell what you\'92re tellin\'92,\'94 Jessie said. \'93This here unit\'92s suered a shame \'92bout that toilet paper.\'94 \'93All week, Mis\'92 Bullitt. We couldn\'92 he\'92p it. You know I got ve girls.\'94 \'93What they been a-doin\'92 with it?\'94 Jessie demanded ominously. \'93Jes\'92 usin\'92 it. Hones\'92, jes\'92 usin\'92 it.\'94 \'93They ain\'92t got the right! Four-ve sheets is enough. What\'92s the matter\'92th \'92em?\'94 The confessor bleated, \'93Skitters. All ve of \'92em. We been low on money. They et green grapes. They all ve got the howlin\'92 skitters. Run out ever\'92 ten minutes.\'94 She defended them, \'93But they ain\'92t stealin\'92 it.\'94 Jessie sighed. \'93You should a tol\'92,\'94 she said. \'93You got to tell. Here\'92s Unit Four suerin\'92 shame \'92cause you never tol\'92. Anybody can git the skitters.\'94 The meek voice whined, \'93I jes\'92 can\'92t keep \'92em from eatin\'92 them green grapes. An\'92 they\'92re a-gettin\'92 worse all a time.\'94 Ella Summers burst out, \'93The Aid. She oughta git the Aid.\'94 \'93Ella Summers,\'94 Jessie said, \'93I\'92m a-tellin\'92 you for the las\'92 time, you ain\'92t the Chair.\'94 She turned back to the raddled little woman. \'93Ain\'92t you got no money, Mis\'92 Joyce?\'94 She looked ashamedly down. \'93No, but we might git work any time.\'94 \'93Now you hol\'92 up your head,\'94 Jessie said. \'93That ain\'92t no crime. You jes\'92 waltz right over t\'92 the Weedpatch store an\'92 git you some grocteries. The camp got twenty dollars\'92 credit there. You git yourself \'92 dollars\'92 worth. An\'92 you kin pay it back to the Central Committee when you git work. Mis\'92 Joyce, you knowed that,\'94 she said sternly. \'93How come you let your girls git hungry?\'94 \'93We ain\'92t never took no charity,\'94 Mrs. Joyce said. \'93This ain\'92t charity, an\'92 you know it,\'94 Jessie raged. \'93We had all that out. They ain\'92t no charity in this here camp. We won\'92t have no charity. Now you waltz right over an\'92 git you some grocteries, an\'92 you bring the slip to me.\'94 Mrs. Joyce said timidly, \'93S\'92pose we can\'92t never pay? We ain\'92t had work for a long time.\'94 \'93You\'92ll pay if you can. If you can\'92t, that ain\'92t none of our business, an\'92 it ain\'92t your business. One fella went away, an\'92 two months later he sent back the money. You ain\'92t got the right to let your girls git hungry in this here camp.\'94 Mrs. Joyce was cowed. \'93Yes, ma\'92am,\'94 she said. \'93Git you some cheese for them girls,\'94 Jessie ordered. \'93That\'92ll take care a them skitters.\'94 \'93Yes, ma\'92am.\'94 And Mrs. Joyce scuttled out of the door. Jessie turned in anger on the committee. \'93She got no right to be sti-necked. She got no right, not with our own people.\'94 Annie Littleeld said, \'93She ain\'92t been here long. Maybe she don\'92t know. Maybe she\'92s took charity one time-another. Nor,\'94 Annie said, \'93don\'92t you try to shut me up, Jessie. I got a right to pass speech.\'94 She turned half to Ma. \'93If a body\'92s ever took charity, it makes a burn that don\'92t come out. This ain\'92t charity, but if you ever took it, you don\'92t forget it. I bet Jessie ain\'92t ever done it.\'94 \'93No, I ain\'92t,\'94 said Jessie. \'93Well, I did,\'94 Annie said. \'93Las\'92 winter; an\'92 we was a-starvin\'92\'97me an\'92 Pa an\'92 the little fellas. An\'92 it was a-rainin\'92. Fella tol\'92 us to go to the Salvation Army.\'94 Her eyes grew erce. \'93We was hungry\'97they made us crawl for our dinner. They took our dignity. They\'97I hate \'92em! An\'92\'97maybe Mis\'92 Joyce took charity. Maybe she didn\'92 know this ain\'92t charity. Mis\'92 Joad, we don\'92t allow nobody in this camp to build their-self up that-a-way. We don\'92t allow nobody to give nothing to another person. They can give it to the camp, an\'92 the camp can pass it out. We won\'92t have no charity!\'94 Her voice was erce and hoarse. \'93I hate \'92em,\'94 she said. \'93I ain\'92t never seen my man beat before, but them\'97them Salvation Army done it to \'92im.\'94 Jessie nodded. \'93I heard,\'94 she said softly, \'93I heard. We got to take Mis\'92 Joad aroun\'92.\'94 Ma said, \'93It sure is nice.\'94 \'93Le\'92s go to the sewin\'92 room,\'94 Annie suggested. \'93Got two machines. They\'92s a-quiltin\'92, an\'92 they\'92re makin\'92 dresses. You might like ta work over there.\'94 When the committee called on Ma, Ruthie and Wineld faded imperceptibly back out of reach. \'93Whyn\'92t we go along an\'92 listen?\'94 Wineld asked. Ruthie gripped his arm. \'93No,\'94 she said. \'93We got washed for them sons-a-bitches. I ain\'92t goin\'92 with \'92em.\'94 Wineld said, \'93You tol\'92 on me \'92bout the toilet. I\'92m a-gonna tell what you called them ladies.\'94 A shadow of fear crossed Ruthie\'92s face. \'93Don\'92 do it. I tol\'92 \'92cause I knowed you didn\'92 really break it.\'94 \'93You did not,\'94 said Wineld. Ruthie said, \'93Le\'92s look aroun\'92.\'94 They strolled down the line of tents, peering into each one, gawking self-consciously. At the end of the unit there was a level place on which a croquet court had been set up. Half a dozen children played seriously. In front of a tent an elderly lady sat on a bench and watched. Ruthie and Wineld broke into a trot. \'93Leave us play,\'94 Ruthie cried. \'93Leave us get in.\'94 The children looked up. A pig-tailed little girl said, \'93Nex\'92 game you kin.\'94 \'93I wanta play now,\'94 Ruthie cried. \'93Well, you can\'92t. Not till nex\'92 game.\'94 Ruthie moved menacingly out on the court. \'93I\'92m a-gonna play.\'94 The pig-tails gripped her mallet tightly. Ruthie sprang at her, slapped her, pushed her, and wrested the mallet from her hands. \'93I says I was gonna play,\'94 she said triumphantly. The elderly lady stood up and walked onto the court. Ruthie scowled ercely and her hands tightened on the mallet. The lady said, \'93Let her play\'97like you done with Ralph las\'92 week.\'94 The children laid their mallets on the ground and trooped silently o the court. They stood at a distance and looked on with expressionless eyes. Ruthie watched them go. Then she hit a ball and ran after it. \'93Come on, Winel\'92. Get a stick,\'94 she called. And then she looked in amazement. Wineld had joined the watching children, and he too looked at her with expressionless eyes. Deantly she hit the ball again. She kicked up a great dust. She pretended to have a good time. And the children stood and watched. Ruthie lined up two balls and hit both of them, and she turned her back on the watching eyes, and then turned back. Suddenly she advanced on them, mallet in hand. \'93You come an\'92 play,\'94 she demanded. They moved silently back at her approach. For a moment she stared at them, and then she ung down the mallet and ran crying for home. The children walked back on the court. Pigtails said to Wineld, \'93You can git in the nex\'92 game.\'94 The watching lady warned them, \'93When she comes back an\'92 wants to be decent, you let her. You was mean yourself, Amy.\'94 The game went on, while in the Joad tent Ruthie wept miserably. The truck moved along the beautiful roads, past orchards where the peaches were beginning to color, past vineyards with the clusters pale and green, under lines of walnut trees whose branches spread half across the road. At each entrance-gate Al slowed; and at each gate there was a sign: \'93No help wanted. No trespassing.\'94 Al said, \'93Pa, they\'92s boun\'92 to be work when them fruits gets ready. Funny place\'97they tell ya they ain\'92t no work \'92fore you ask \'92em.\'94 He drove slowly on. Pa said, \'93Maybe we could go in anyways an\'92 ask if they know where they\'92s any work. Might do that.\'94 A man in blue overalls and a blue shirt walked along the edge of the road. Al pulled up beside him. \'93Hey, mister,\'94 Al said. \'93Know where they\'92s any work?\'94 The man stopped and grinned, and his mouth was vacant of front teeth. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93Do you? I been walkin\'92 all week, an\'92 I can\'92t tree none.\'94 \'93Live in that gov\'92ment camp?\'94 Al asked. \'93Yeah!\'94 \'93Come on, then. Git up back, an\'92 we\'92ll all look.\'94 The man climbed over the side-boards and dropped in the bed. Pa said, \'93I ain\'92t got no hunch we\'92ll nd work. Guess we got to look, though. We don\'92t even know where-at to look.\'94 \'93Shoulda talked to the fellas in the camp,\'94 Al said. \'93How you feelin\'92, Uncle John?\'94 \'93I ache,\'94 said Uncle John. \'93I ache all over, an\'92 I got it comin\'92. I oughta go away where I won\'92t bring down punishment on my own folks.\'94 Pa put his hand on John\'92s knee. \'93Look