n we\'92d get a tent, big enough, an\'92 maybe secon\'92-han\'92 springs for the beds. An\'92 we\'92d use this here tent jus\'92 to eat under. An\'92 Sat\'92dy night we\'92ll go to the dancin\'92. They says you can invite folks if you want. I wisht we had some frien\'92s to invite. Maybe the men\'92ll know somebody to invite.\'94 Rose of Sharon peered down the road. \'93That lady that says I\'92ll lose the baby\'97\'94 she began. \'93Now you stop that,\'94 Ma warned her. Rose of Sharon said softly, \'93I seen her. She\'92s a-comin\'92 here, I think. Yeah! Here she comes. Ma, don\'92t let her\'97\'97\'94 Ma turned and looked at the approaching gure. \'93Howdy,\'94 the woman said. \'93I\'92m Mis\'92 Sandry\'97Lisbeth Sandry. I seen your girl this mornin\'92.\'94 \'93Howdy do,\'94 said Ma. \'93Are you happy in the Lord?\'94 \'93Pretty happy,\'94 said Ma. \'93Are you saved?\'94 \'93I been saved.\'94 Ma\'92s face was closed and waiting. \'93Well, I\'92m glad,\'94 Lisbeth said. \'93The sinners is awful strong aroun\'92 here. You come to a awful place. They\'92s wicketness all around about. Wicket people, wicket goin\'92s-on that a lamb\'92-blood Christian jes\'92 can\'92t hardly stan\'92. They\'92s sinners all around us.\'94 Ma colored a little, and shut her mouth tightly. \'93Seems to me they\'92s nice people here,\'94 she said shortly. Mrs. Sandry\'92s eyes stared. \'93Nice!\'94 she cried. \'93You think they\'92re nice when they\'92s dancin\'92 an\'92 huggin\'92? I tell ya, ya eternal soul ain\'92t got a chancet in this here camp. Went out to a meetin\'92 in Weedpatch las\'92 night. Know what the preacher says? He says, \'91They\'92s wicketness in that camp.\'92 He says, \'91The poor is tryin\'92 to be rich.\'92 He says, \'91They\'92s dancin\'92 an\'92 huggin\'92 when they should be wailin\'92 an\'92 moanin\'92 in sin.\'92 That\'92s what he says. \'91Ever\'92body that ain\'92t here is a black sinner,\'92 he says. I tell you it made a person feel purty good to hear \'92im. An\'92 we knowed we was safe. We ain\'92t danced.\'94 Ma\'92s face was red. She stood up slowly and faced Mrs. Sandry. \'93Git!\'94 she said. \'93Git out now, \'92fore I git to be a sinner a-tellin\'92 you where to go. Git to your wailin\'92 an\'92 moanin\'92.\'94 Mrs. Sandry\'92s mouth dropped open. She stepped back. And then she became erce. \'93I thought you was Christians.\'94 \'93So we are,\'94 Ma said. \'93No, you ain\'92t. You\'92re hell-burnin\'92 sinners, all of you! An\'92 I\'92ll mention it in meetin\'92, too. I can see your black soul a-burnin\'92. I can see that innocent child in that there girl\'92s belly a-burnin\'92.\'94 A low wailing cry escaped from Rose of Sharon\'92s lips. Ma stooped down and picked up a stick of wood. \'93Git!\'94 she said coldly. \'93Don\'92 you never come back. I seen your kind before. You\'92d take the little pleasure, wouldn\'92 you?\'94 Ma advanced on Mrs. Sandry. For a moment the woman backed away and then suddenly she threw back her head and howled. Her eyes rolled up, her shoulders and arms opped loosely at her side, and a string of thick ropy saliva ran from the corner of her mouth. She howled again and again, long deep animal howls. Men and women ran up from the other tents, and they stood near\'97frightened and quiet. Slowly the woman sank to her knees and the howls sank to a shuddering, bubbling moan. She fell sideways and her arms and legs twitched. The white eye-balls showed under the open eyelids. A man said softly, \'93The sperit. She got the sperit.\'94 Ma stood looking down at the twitching form. The little manager strolled up casually. \'93Trouble?\'94 he asked. The crowd parted to let him through. He looked down at the woman. \'93Too bad,\'94 he said. \'93Will some of you help get her back to her tent?\'94 The silent people shued their feet. Two men bent over and lifted the woman, one held her under the arms and the other took her feet. They carried her away, and the people moved slowly after them. Rose of