d, gentle and sighing, blew in pus from the southwest, and the mountains on both sides of the great valley were indistinct in a pearly mist. Tom was pumping at the tire when a roadster, coming from the north, stopped on the other side of the road. A brown-faced man dressed in a light gray business suit got out and walked across to the truck. He was bareheaded. He smiled, and his teeth were very white against his brown skin. He wore a massive gold wedding ring on the third nger of his left hand. A little gold football hung on a slender chain across his vest. \'93Morning,\'94 he said pleasantly. Tom stopped pumping and looked up. \'93Mornin\'92.\'94 The man ran his ngers through his coarse, short, graying hair. \'93You people looking for work?\'94 \'93We sure are, mister. Lookin\'92 even under boards.\'94 \'93Can you pick peaches?\'94 \'93We never done it,\'94 Pa said. \'93We can do anything,\'94 Tom said hurriedly. \'93We can pick anything there is.\'94 The man ngered his gold football. \'93Well, there\'92s plenty of work for you about forty miles north.\'94 \'93We\'92d sure admire to get it,\'94 said Tom. \'93You tell us how to get there, an\'92 we\'92ll go a-lopin\'92.\'94 \'93Well, you go north to Pixley, that\'92s thirty-ve or -six miles, and you turn east. Go about six miles. Ask anybody where the Hooper ranch is. You\'92ll nd plenty of work there.\'94 \'93We sure will.\'94 \'93Know where there\'92s other people looking for work?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said Tom. \'93Down at the Weedpatch camp they\'92s plenty lookin\'92 for work.\'94 \'93I\'92ll take a run down there. We can use quite a few. Remember now, turn east at Pixley and keep straight east to the Hooper ranch.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said Tom. \'93An\'92 we thank ya, mister. We need work awful bad.\'94 \'93All right. Get along as soon as you can.\'94 He walked back across the road, climbed into his open roadster, and drove away south. Tom threw his weight on the pump. \'93Twenty apiece,\'94 he called. \'93One\'97tw