\'94 \'93An\'92 coee,\'94 said Tom. \'93Might even get me a sack a Durham. I ain\'92t had no tobacca of my own for a long time.\'94 Far ahead the road was blocked with cars, and a line of white motorcycles was drawn up along the roadside. \'93Mus\'92 be a wreck,\'94 Tom said. As they drew near a State policeman, in boots and Sam Browne belt, stepped around the last parked car. He held up his hand and Al pulled to a stop. The policeman leaned condentially on the side of the car. \'93Where you going?\'94 Al said, \'93Fella said they was work pickin\'92 peaches up this way.\'94 \'93Want to work, do you?\'94 \'93Damn right,\'94 said Tom. \'93O.K. Wait here a minute.\'94 He moved to the side of the road and called ahead. \'93One more. That\'92s six cars ready. Better take this batch through.\'94 Tom called, \'93Hey! What\'92s the matter?\'94 The patrol man lounged back. \'93Got a little trouble up ahead. Don\'92t you worry. You\'92ll get through. Just follow the line.\'94 There came the splattering blast of motorcycles starting. The line of cars moved on, with the Joad truck last. Two motorcycles led the way, and two followed. Tom said uneasily, \'93I wonder what\'92s a matter.\'94 \'93Maybe the road\'92s out,\'94 Al suggested. \'93Don\'92 need four cops to lead us. I don\'92 like it.\'94 The motorcycles ahead speeded up. The line of old cars speeded up. Al hurried to keep in back of the last car. \'93These here is our own people, all of \'92em,\'94 Tom said. \'93I don\'92 like this.\'94 Suddenly the leading policemen turned o the road into a wide graveled entrance. The old cars whipped after them. The motorcycles roared their motors. Tom saw a line of men standing in the ditch beside the road, saw their mouths open as though they were yelling, saw their shaking sts and their furious faces. A stout woman ran toward the cars, but a roaring motorcycle stood in her way. A high wire gate swung open. The six old cars moved through and the gate closed behind them. The four motorcycles turned and sped back in the direction from which they had come. And now that the motors were gone, the distant yelling of the men in the ditch could be heard. Two men stood beside the graveled road. Each one carried a shotgun. One called, \'93Go on, go on. What the hell are you waiting for?\'94 The six cars moved ahead, turned a bend and came suddenly on the peach camp. There were fty little square, at-roofed boxes, each with a door and a window, and the whole group in a square. A water tank stood high on one edge of the camp. And a little grocery store stood on the other side. At the end of each row of square houses stood two men armed with shotguns and wearing big silver stars pinned to their shirts. The six cars stopped. Two bookkeepers moved from car to car. \'93Want to work?\'94 Tom answered, \'93Sure, but what is this?\'94 \'93That\'92s not your aair. Want to work?\'94 \'93Sure we do.\'94 \'93Name?\'94 \'93Joad.\'94 \'93How many men?\'94 \'93Four.\'94 \'93Women?\'94 \'93Two.\'94 \'93Kids?\'94 \'93Two.\'94 \'93Can all of you work?\'94 \'93Why\'97I guess so.\'94 \'93O.K. Find house sixty-three. Wages ve cents a box. No bruised fruit. All right, move along now. Go to work right away.\'94 The cars moved on. On the door of each square red house a number was painted. \'93Sixty,\'94 Tom said. \'93There\'92s sixty. Must be down that way. There, sixty-one, sixty-two\'97There she is.\'94 Al parked the truck close to the door of the little house. The family came down from the top of the truck and looked about in bewilderment. Two deputies approached. They looked closely into each face. \'93Name?\'94 \'93Joad,\'94 Tom said impatiently. \'93Say, what is this here?\'94 One of the deputies took out a long list. \'93Not here. Ever see these here? Look at the license. Nope. Ain\'92t got it. Guess they\'92re O.K.\'94 \'93Now you look here. We don\'92t want no trouble with you. Jes\'92 do your work and mind your own business and you\'92ll be all right.\'94 The two turned abruptly and walked away. At the end of the dusty street they sat down on two boxes and their position commanded the length of the street. Tom stared after them. \'93They sure do wanta make us feel at home.\'94 Ma opened the door of the house and stepped inside. The oor was splashed with grease. In the one room stood a rusty tin stove and nothing more. The tin stove rested on four bricks and its rusty stovepipe went up through the roof. The room smelled of sweat and grease. Rose of Sharon stood beside Ma. \'93We gonna live here?\'94 Ma was silent for a moment. \'93Why, sure,\'94 she said at last. \'93It ain\'92t so bad once we wash it out. Get her mopped.\'94 \'93I like the tent better,\'94 the girl said. \'93This got a oor,\'94 Ma suggested. \'93This here wouldn\'92 leak when it rains.\'94 She turned to the door. \'93Might as well unload,\'94 she said. The men unloaded the truck silently. A fear had fallen on them. The great square of boxes was silent. A woman went by in the street, but she did not look at them. Her head was sunk and her dirty gingham dress was frayed at the bottom in little ags. The pall had fallen on Ruthie and Wineld. They did not dash away to inspect the place. They stayed close to the truck, close to the family. They looked forlornly up and down the dusty street. Wineld found a piece of baling wire and he bent it back and forth until it broke. He made a little crank of the shortest piece and turned it around and around in his hands. Tom and Pa were carrying the mattresses into the house when a clerk appeared. He wore khaki trousers and a blue shirt and a black necktie. He wore silver-bound eyeglasses, and his eyes, through the thick lenses, were weak and red, and the pupils were staring little bull\'92s eyes. He leaned forward to look at Tom. \'93I want to get you checked down,\'94 he said. \'93How many of you going to work?\'94 Tom said, \'93They\'92s four men. Is this here hard work?\'94 \'93Picking peaches,\'94 the clerk said. \'93Piece work. Give ve cents a box.\'94 \'93Ain\'92t no reason why the little fellas can\'92t help?\'94 \'93Sure not, if they\'92re careful.\'94 Ma stood in the doorway. \'93Soon\'92s I get settled down I\'92ll come out an\'92 help. We got nothin\'92 to eat, mister. Do we get paid right o ?\'94 \'93Well, no, not money right o. But you can get credit at the store for what you got coming.\'94 \'93Come on, let\'92s hurry,\'94 Tom said. \'93I want ta get some meat an\'92 bread in me tonight. Where do we go, mister?\'94 \'93I\'92m going out there now. Come with me.\'94 Tom and Pa and Al and Uncle John walked with him down the dusty street and into the orchard, in among the peach trees. The narrow leaves were beginning to turn a pale yellow. The peaches were little globes of gold and red on the branches. Among the trees were piles of empty boxes. The pickers scurried about, lling their buckets from the branches, putting the peaches in the boxes, carrying the boxes to the checking station; and at the stations, where the piles of lled boxes waited for the trucks, clerks waited to check against the names of the pickers. \'93Here\'92s four more,\'94 the guide said to a clerk. \'93O.K. Ever picked before?\'94 \'93Never did,\'94 said Tom. \'93Well, pick careful. No bruised fruit, no windfalls. Bruise your fruit an\'92 we won\'92t check \'92em. There\'92s some buckets.\'94 Tom picked up a three-gallon bucket and looked at it. \'93Full a holes on the bottom.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said the near-sighted clerk. \'93That keeps people from stealing them. All right\'97down in that section. Get going.\'94 The four Joads took their buckets and went into the orchard. \'93They don\'92t waste no time,\'94 Tom said. \'93Christ Awmighty,\'94 Al said. \'93I ruther work in a garage.\'94 Pa had followed docilely into the eld. He turned suddenly on Al. \'93Now you jus\'92 quit it,\'94 he said. \'93You been a-hankerin\'92 an\'92 acomplainin\'92 an\'92 a-bullblowin\'92. You get to work. You ain\'92t so big I can