on\'92t give a damn \'92bout steps up or down or sideways.\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 said Casy. \'93Sure. He\'92s jus\'92 doin\'92 what he\'92s got to do. All of us like that.\'94 The man seated outside pulled the tent ap wide. \'93Goddamn it, I don\'92 like it,\'94 he said. Casy looked out at him. \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 \'93I don\'92 know. I jus\'92 itch all over. Nervous as a cat.\'94 \'93Well, what\'92s the matter?\'94 \'93I don\'92 know. Seems like I hear somepin, an\'92 then I listen an\'92 they ain\'92t nothin\'92 to hear.\'94 \'93You\'92re jus\'92 jumpy,\'94 the wizened man said. He got up and went outside. And in a second he looked into the tent. \'93They\'92s a great big ol\'92 black cloud a-sailin\'92 over. Bet she\'92s got thunder. That\'92s what\'92s itchin\'92 him \'97\'92lectricity.\'94 He ducked out again. The other two men stood up from the ground and went outside. Casy said softly, \'93All of \'92em\'92s itchy. Them cops been sayin\'92 how they\'92re gonna beat the hell outa us an\'92 run us outa the county. They gger I\'92m a leader \'92cause I talk so much.\'94 The wizened face looked in again. \'93Casy, turn out that lantern an\'92 come outside. They\'92s somepin.\'94 Casy turned the screw. The ame drew down into the slots and popped and went out. Casy groped outside and Tom followed him. \'93What is it?\'94 Casy asked softly. \'93I dunno. Listen!\'94 There was a wall of frog sounds that merged with silence. A high, shrill whistle of crickets. But through this background came other sounds\'97faint footsteps from the road, a crunch of clods up on the bank, a little swish of brush down the stream. \'93Can\'92t really tell if you hear it. Fools you. Get nervous,\'94 Casy reassured them. \'93We\'92re all nervous. Can\'92t really tell. You hear it, Tom?\'94 \'93I hear it,\'94 said Tom. \'93Yeah, I hear it. I think they\'92s guys comin\'92 from ever\'92 which way. We better get outa here.\'94 The wizened man whispered, \'93Under the bridge span\'97out that way. Hate to leave my tent.\'94 \'93Le\'92s go,\'94 said Casy. They moved quietly along the edge of the stream. The black span was a cave before them. Casy bent over and moved through. Tom behind. Their feet slipped into the water. Thirty feet they moved, and their breathing echoed from the curved ceiling. Then they came out on the other side and straightened up. A sharp call, \'93There they are!\'94 Two ashlight beams fell on the men, caught them, blinded them. \'93Stand where you are.\'94 The voices came out of the darkness. \'93That\'92s him. That shiny bastard. That\'92s him.\'94 Casy stared blindly at the light. He breathed heavily. \'93Listen,\'94 he said. \'93You fellas don\'92 know what you\'92re doin\'92. You\'92re helpin\'92 to starve kids.\'94 \'93Shut up, you red son-of-a-bitch.\'94 A short heavy man stepped into the light. He carried a new white pick handle. Casy went on, \'93You don\'92 know what you\'92re a-doin\'92.\'94 The heavy man swung with the pick handle. Casy dodged down into the swing. The heavy club crashed into the side of his head with a dull crunch of bone, and Casy fell sideways out of the light. \'93Jesus, George. I think you killed him.\'94 \'93Put the light on him,\'94 said George. \'93Serve the son-of-a-bitch right.\'94 The ashlight beam dropped, searched and found Casy\'92s crushed head. Tom looked down at the preacher. The light crossed the heavy man\'92s legs and the white new pick handle. Tom leaped silently. He wrenched the club free. The rst time he knew he had missed and struck a shoulder, but the second time his crushing blow found the head, and as the heavy man sank down, three more blows found his head. The lights danced about. There were shouts, the sound of running feet, crashing through brush. Tom stood over the prostrate man. And then a club reached his head, a glancing blow. He felt the stroke like an electric shock. And then he was running along the stream, bending low. He heard the splash of footsteps following h