e gonna have her baby an\'92 they won\'92t be no fambly. I don\'92 know. I been a-tryin\'92 to keep her goin\'92. Winel\'92\'97what\'92s he gonna be, this-a-way? Gettin\'92 wild, an\'92 Ruthie too\'97like animals. Got nothin\'92 to trus\'92. Don\'92 go, Tom. Stay an\'92 help.\'94 \'93O.K.,\'94 he said tiredly. \'93O.K. I shouldn\'92, though. I know it.\'94 Ma went to her dishpan and washed the tin plates and dried them. \'93You didn\'92 sleep.\'94 \'93No.\'94 \'93Well, you sleep. I seen your clothes was wet. I\'92ll hang \'92em by the stove to dry.\'94 She nished her work. \'93I\'92m goin\'92 now. I\'92ll pick. Rosasharn, if anybody comes, Tom\'92s sick, you hear? Don\'92 let nobody in. You hear?\'94 Rose of Sharon nodded. \'93We\'92ll come back at noon. Get some sleep, Tom. Maybe we can get outa here tonight.\'94 She moved swiftly to him. \'93Tom, you ain\'92t gonna slip out?\'94 \'93No, Ma.\'94 \'93You sure? You won\'92t go?\'94 \'93No, Ma. I\'92ll be here.\'94 \'93Awright. \'92Member, Rosasharn.\'94 She went out and closed the door rmly behind her. Tom lay still\'97and then a wave of sleep lifted him to the edge of unconsciousness and dropped him slowly back and lifted him again. \'93You\'97Tom!\'94 \'93Huh? Yeah!\'94 He started awake. He looked over at Rose of Sharon. Her eyes were blazing with resentment. \'93What you want?\'94 \'93You killed a fella!\'94 \'93Yeah. Not so loud! You wanta rouse somebody?\'94 \'93What da I care?\'94 she cried. \'93That lady tol\'92 me. She says what sin\'92s gonna do. She tol\'92 me. What chance I got to have a nice baby? Connie\'92s gone, an\'92 I ain\'92t gettin\'92 good food. I ain\'92t gettin\'92 milk.\'94 Her voice rose hysterically. \'93An\'92 now you kill a fella. What chance that baby got to get bore right? I know\'97gonna be a freak\'97a freak! I never done no dancin\'92.\'94 Tom got up. \'93Sh!\'94 he said. \'93You\'92re gonna get folks in here.\'94 \'93I don\'92 care. I\'92ll have a freak! I didn\'92 dance no hug-dance