2t nobody get in.\'94 He studied her face for a moment. \'93O.K.,\'94 he said, and he covered his face with the blanket again. In the beginning dusk Ma came back to the house. She paused on the doorstep and knocked and said, \'93It\'92s me,\'94 so that Tom would not be worried. She opened the door and entered, carrying a bag. Tom awakened and sat up on his mattress. His wound had dried and tightened so that the unbroken skin was shiny. His left eye was drawn nearly shut. \'93Anybody come while we was gone?\'94 Ma asked. \'93No,\'94 he said. \'93Nobody. I see they dropped the price.\'94 \'93How\'92d you know?\'94 \'93I heard folks talkin\'92 outside.\'94 Rose of Sharon looked dully up at Ma. Tom pointed at her with his thumb. \'93She raised hell, Ma. Thinks all the trouble is aimed right smack at her. If I\'92m gonna get her upset like that I oughta go \'92long.\'94 Ma turned on Rose of Sharon. \'93What you doin\'92?\'94 The girl said resentfully, \'93How\'92m I gonna have a nice baby with stu like this?\'94 Ma said, \'93Hush! You hush now. I know how you\'92re a-feelin\'92, an\'92 I know you can\'92t he\'92p it, but you jus\'92 keep your mouth shut.\'94 She turned back to Tom. \'93Don\'92t pay her no mind, Tom. It\'92s awful hard, an\'92 I \'92member how it is. Ever\'92thing is a-shootin\'92 right at you when you\'92re gonna have a baby, an\'92 ever\'92thing anybody says is a insult, an\'92 ever\'92thing\'92s against you. Don\'92t pay no mind. She can\'92t he\'92p it. It\'92s jus\'92 the way she feels.\'94 \'93I don\'92 wanta hurt her.\'94 \'93Hush! Jus\'92 don\'92 talk.\'94 She set her bag down on the cold stove. \'93Didn\'92 hardly make nothin\'92,\'94 she said. \'93I tol\'92 you, we\'92re gonna get outa here. Tom, try an\'92 wrassle me some wood. No\'97you can\'92t. Here, we got on\'92y this one box lef\'92. Break it up. I tol\'92 the other fellas to pick up some sticks on the way back. Gonna have mush an\'92 a little sugar on.\'94 Tom got up and stamped the last