'94 \'93No, here, give \'92im to me.\'94 She hoisted the little boy and turned back; and then she remembered herself. \'93I sure thank ya,\'94 she said to the men. \'93Welcome, ma\'92am. The little fella\'92s purty weak. Looks like he got worms.\'94 Ma hurried back, and Wineld was limp and relaxed in her arms. Ma carried him into the house and knelt down and laid him on a mattress. \'93Tell me. What\'92s the matter?\'94 she demanded. He opened his eyes dizzily and shook his head and closed his eyes again. Ruthie said, \'93I tol\'92 ya, Ma. He skittered all day. Ever\'92 little while. Et too many peaches.\'94 Ma felt his head. \'93He ain\'92t fevered. But he\'92s white and drawed out.\'94 Tom came near and held the lantern down. \'93I know,\'94 he said. \'93He\'92s hungered. Got no strength. Get him a can a milk an\'92 make him drink it. Make \'92im take milk on his mush.\'94 \'93Winel\'92,\'94 Ma said. \'93Tell how ya feel.\'94 \'93Dizzy,\'94 said Wineld, \'93jus\'92 a-whirlin\'92 dizzy.\'94 \'93You never seen sech skitters,\'94 Ruthie said importantly. Pa and Uncle John and Al came into the house. Their arms were full of sticks and bits of brush. They dropped their loads by the stove. \'93Now what?\'94 Pa demanded. \'93It\'92s Winel\'92. He needs some milk.\'94 \'93Christ Awmighty! We all need stu!\'94 Ma said, \'93How much\'92d we make today?\'94 \'93Dollar forty-two.\'94 \'93Well, you go right over\'92n get a can a milk for Winel\'92.\'94 \'93Now why\'92d he have to get sick?\'94 \'93I don\'92t know why, but he is. Now you git!\'94 Pa went grumbling out the door. \'93You stirrin\'92 that mush?\'94 \'93Yeah.\'94 Rose of Sharon speeded up the stirring to prove it. Al complained, \'93God Awmighty, Ma! Is mush all we get after workin\'92 till dark?\'94 \'93Al, you know we got to git. Take all we got for gas. You know.\'94 \'93But, God Awmighty, Ma! A fella needs meat if he\'92s gonna work.\'94 \'93Jus\'92 you sit quiet,\'94 she said. \'93We got to take the bigges\'92