he hot black coee into the cups and passed them around. \'93Now will you tell what\'92s goin\'92 on?\'94 Tom asked. \'93I wanta hear.\'94 Pa said uneasily, \'93I wisht Ruthie an\'92 Winel\'92 didn\'92 hafta hear. Can\'92t they go outside?\'94 Ma said, \'93No. They got to act growed up, even if they ain\'92t. They\'92s no help for it. Ruthie\'97you an\'92 Winel\'92 ain\'92t ever to say what you hear, else you\'92ll jus\'92 break us to pieces.\'94 \'93We won\'92t,\'94 Ruthie said. \'93We\'92re growed up.\'94 \'93Well, jus\'92 be quiet, then.\'94 The cups of coee were on the oor. The short thick ame of the lantern, like a stubby buttery\'92s wing, cast a yellow gloom on the walls. \'93Now tell,\'94 said Tom. Ma said, \'93Pa, you tell.\'94 Uncle John slupped his coee. Pa said, \'93Well, they dropped the price like you said. An\'92 they was a whole slew a new pickers so goddamn hungry they\'92d pick for a loaf a bread. Go for a peach, an\'92 somebody\'92d get it rst. Gonna get the whole crop picked right o. Fellas runnin\'92 to a new tree. I seen ghts\'97one fella claims it\'92s his tree, \'92nother fella wants to pick o \'92n it. Brang these here folks from as far\'92s El Centro. Hungrier\'92n hell. Work all day for a piece a bread. I says to the checker, \'91We can\'92t work for two an\'92 a half cents a box,\'92 an\'92 he says, \'91Go on, then, quit. These fellas can.\'92 I says, \'91Soon\'92s they get fed up they won\'92t.\'92 An\'92 he says, \'91Hell, we\'92ll have these here peaches in \'92fore they get fed up.\'94\'92 Pa stopped. \'93She was a devil,\'94 said Uncle John. \'93They say they\'92s two hunderd more men comin\'92 in tonight.\'94 Tom said, \'93Yeah! But how about the other?\'94 Pa was silent for a while. \'93Tom,\'94 he said, \'93looks like you done it.\'94 \'93I kinda thought so. Couldn\'92 see. Felt like it.\'94 \'93Seems like the people ain\'92t talkin\'92 \'92bout much else,\'94 said Uncle John. \'93They got posses out, an\'92 they\'92s fellas talkin\'92 up a lynchin\'92\'97\'92course when they catch the fella.\'94 Tom looked over at the wide-eyed children. They seldom blinked their eyes. It was as though they were afraid something might happen in the split second of darkness. Tom said, \'93Well\'97this fella that done it, he on\'92y done it after they killed Casy.\'94 Pa interrupted, \'93That ain\'92t the way they\'92re tellin\'92 it now. They\'92re sayin\'92 he done it fust.\'94 Tom\'92s breath sighed out, \'93Ah-h!\'94 \'93They\'92re workin\'92 up a feelin\'92 against us folks. That\'92s what I heard. All them drum-corpse fellas an\'92 lodges an\'92 all that. Say they\'92re gonna get this here fella.\'94 \'93They know what he looks like?\'94 Tom asked. \'93Well\'97not exactly\'97but the way I heard it, they think he got hit. They think\'97he\'92ll have\'97\'97\'94 Tom put his hand up slowly and touched his bruised cheek. Ma cried, \'93It ain\'92t so, what they say!\'94 \'93Easy, Ma,\'94 Tom said. \'93They got it cold. Anything them drumcorpse fellas say is right if it\'92s against us.\'94 Ma peered through the ill light, and she watched Tom\'92s face, and particularly his lips. \'93You promised,\'94 she said. \'93Ma, I\'97maybe this fella oughta go away. If\'97this fella done somepin wrong, maybe he\'92d think, \'91O.K. Le\'92s get the hangin\'92 over. I done wrong an\'92 I got to take it.\'92 But this fella didn\'92 do nothin\'92 wrong. He don\'92 feel no worse\'92n if he killed a skunk.\'94 Ruthie broke in, \'93Ma, me an\'92 Winel\'92 knows. He don\'92 have to go this-fella\'92in\'92 for us.\'94 Tom chuckled. \'93Well, this fella don\'92 want no hangin\'92, \'92cause he\'92d do it again. An\'92 same time, he don\'92t aim to bring trouble down on his folks. Ma\'97I got to go.\'94 Ma covered her mouth with her ngers and coughed to clear her throat. \'93You can\'92t,\'94 she said. \'93They wouldn\'92 be no way to hide out. You couldn\'92 trus\'92 nobody. But you can trus\'92 us. We can hide you, an\'92 we can