ou mean that hitch-hiker? Little short fella with a pale face?\'94 \'93Yeah. I guess that\'92s what he looked like.\'94 \'93We jus\'92 picked him up on the way in. He went away this mornin\'92 when the rate dropped.\'94 \'93What did he look like again?\'94 \'93Short fella. Pale face.\'94 \'93Was he bruised up this mornin\'92?\'94 \'93I didn\'92 see nothin\'92,\'94 said Al. \'93Is the gas pump open?\'94 \'93Yeah, till eight.\'94 \'93Git in,\'94 Al cried. \'93If we\'92re gonna get to Weedpatch \'92fore mornin\'92 we gotta ram on. Gettin\'92 in front, Ma?\'94 \'93No, I\'92ll set in back,\'94 she said. \'93Pa, you set back here too. Let Rosasharn set in front with Al an\'92 Uncle John.\'94 \'93Give me the work slip, Pa,\'94 said Al. \'93I\'92ll get gas an\'92 change if I can.\'94 The guard watched them pull along the street and turn left to the gasoline pumps. \'93Put in two,\'94 said Al. \'93You ain\'92t goin\'92 far.\'94 \'93No, not far. Can I get change on this here work slip?\'94 \'93Well\'97I ain\'92t supposed to.\'94 \'93Look, mister,\'94 Al said. \'93We got a good job oered if we get there tonight. If we don\'92t, we miss out. Be a good fella.\'94 \'93Well, O.K. You sign her over to me.\'94 Al got out and walked around the nose of the Hudson. \'93Sure I will,\'94 he said. He unscrewed the water cap and lled the radiator. \'93Two, you say?\'94 \'93Yeah, two.\'94 \'93Which way you goin\'92?\'94 \'93South. We got a job.\'94 \'93Yeah? Jobs is scarce\'97reg\'92lar jobs.\'94 \'93We got a frien\'92,\'94 Al said. \'93Job\'92s all waitin\'92 for us. Well, so long.\'94 The truck swung around and bumped over the dirt street into the road. The feeble headlight jiggled over the way, and the right headlight blinked on and o from a bad connection. At every jolt the loose pots and pans in the truck-bed jangled and crashed. Rose of Sharon moaned softly. \'93Feel bad?\'94 Uncle John asked. \'93Yeah! Feel bad all a time. Wisht I could set still in a nice place. Wisht we was home an