ot to, Tom.\'94 \'93Then come along. Come quiet.\'94 He crossed the little stream, wading carelessly through the water, and Ma followed him. He moved through the brush, out into a eld on the other side of the thicket, and along the plowed ground. The blackening stems of the cotton were harsh against the ground, and a few us of cotton clung to the stems. A quarter of a mile they went along the edge of the eld, and then he turned into the brush again. He approached a great mound of wild blackberry bushes, leaned over and pulled a mat of vines aside. \'93You got to crawl in,\'94 he said. Ma went down on her hands and knees. She felt sand under her, and then the black inside of the mound no longer touched her, and she felt Tom\'92s blanket on the ground. He arranged the vines in place again. It was lightless in the cave. \'93Where are you, Ma?\'94 \'93Here. Right here. Talk soft, Tom.\'94 \'93Don\'92t worry. I been livin\'92 like a rabbit some time.\'94 She heard him unwrap his tin plate. \'93Pork chops,\'94 she said. \'93And fry potatoes.\'94 \'93God Awmighty, an\'92 still warm.\'94 Ma could not see him at all in the blackness, but she could hear him chewing, tearing at the meat and swallowing. \'93It\'92s a pretty good hide-out,\'94 he said. Ma said uneasily, \'93Tom\'97Ruthie tol\'92 about you.\'94 She heard him gulp. \'93Ruthie? What for?\'94 \'93Well, it wasn\'92 her fault. Got in a ght, an\'92 says her brother\'92ll lick that other girl\'92s brother. You know how they do. An\'92 she tol\'92 that her brother killed a man an\'92 was hidin\'92.\'94 Tom was chuckling. \'93With me I was always gonna get Uncle John after \'92em, but he never would do it. That\'92s jus\'92 kid talk, Ma. That\'92s awright.\'94 \'93No, it ain\'92t,\'94 Ma said. \'93Them kids\'92ll tell it aroun\'92 an\'92 then the folks\'92ll hear, an\'92 they\'92ll tell aroun\'92, an\'92 pretty soon, well, they liable to get men out to look, jus\'92 in case. Tom, you got to go away.\'94 \'93That\'92s what