2 what he said, an\'92 I can remember\'97all of it. Says one time he went out in the wilderness to nd his own soul, an\'92 he foun\'92 he didn\'92 have no soul that was his\'92n. Says he foun\'92 he jus\'92 got a little piece of a great big soul. Says a wilderness ain\'92t no good, \'92cause his little piece of a soul wasn\'92t no good \'92less it was with the rest, an\'92 was whole. Funny how I remember. Didn\'92 think I was even listenin\'92. But I know now a fella ain\'92t no good alone.\'94 \'93He was a good man,\'94 Ma said. Tom went on, \'93He spouted out some Scripture once, an\'92 it didn\'92 soun\'92 like no hell-re Scripture. He tol\'92 it twicet, an\'92 I remember it. Says it\'92s from the Preacher.\'94 \'93How\'92s it go, Tom?\'94 \'93Goes, \'91Two are better than one, because they have a good reward for their labor. For if they fall, the one will lif\'92 up his fellow, but woe to him that is alone when he falleth, for he hath not another to help him up.\'92 That\'92s part of her.\'94 \'93Go on,\'94 Ma said. \'93Go on, Tom.\'94 \'93Jus\'92 a little bit more. \'91Again, if two lie together, then they have heat: but how can one be warm alone? And if one prevail against him, two shall withstand him, and a three-fold cord is not quickly broken.\'94\'92 \'93An\'92 that\'92s Scripture?\'94 \'93Casy said it was. Called it the Preacher.\'94 \'93Hush\'97listen.\'94 \'93On\'92y the wind, Ma. I know the wind. An\'92 I got to thinkin\'92, Ma\'97 most of the preachin\'92 is about the poor we shall have always with us, an\'92 if you got nothin\'92, why, jus\'92 fol\'92 your hands an\'92 to hell with it, you gonna git ice cream on gol\'92 plates when you\'92re dead. An\'92 then this here Preacher says two get a better reward for their work.\'94 \'93Tom,\'94 she said. \'93What you aimin\'92 to do?\'94 He was quiet for a long time. \'93I been thinkin\'92 how it was in that gov\'92ment camp, how our folks took care a theirselves, an\'92 if they was a ght they xed it theirself; an\'92 they wasn\'92t no cops wagglin\'92 their guns, but they was better order than them cops ever give. I been a-wonderin\'92 why we can\'92t do that all over. Throw out the cops that ain\'92t our people. All work together for our own thing\'97all farm our own lan\'92.\'94 \'93Tom,\'94 Ma repeated, \'93what you gonna do?\'94 \'93What Casy done,\'94 he said. \'93But they killed him.\'94 \'93Yeah,\'94 said Tom. \'93He didn\'92 duck quick enough. He wasn\'92 doing nothin\'92 against the law, Ma. I been thinkin\'92 a hell of a lot, thinkin\'92 about our people livin\'92 like pigs, an\'92 the good rich lan\'92 layin\'92 fallow, or maybe one fella with a million acres, while a hunderd thousan\'92 good farmers is starvin\'92. An\'92 I been wonderin\'92 if all our folks got together an\'92 yelled, like them fellas yelled, only a few of \'92em at the Hooper ranch\'97\'97\'94 Ma said, \'93Tom, they\'92ll drive you, an\'92 cut you down like they done to young Floyd.\'94 \'93They gonna drive me anyways. They drivin\'92 all our people.\'94 \'93You don\'92t aim to kill nobody, Tom?\'94 \'93No. I been thinkin\'92, long as I\'92m a outlaw anyways, maybe I could \'97Hell, I ain\'92t thought it out clear, Ma. Don\'92 worry me now. Don\'92 worry me.\'94 They sat silent in the coal-black cave of vines. Ma said, \'93How\'92m I gonna know \'92bout you? They might kill ya an\'92 I wouldn\'92 know. They might hurt ya. How\'92m I gonna know?\'94 Tom laughed uneasily, \'93Well, maybe like Casy says, a fella ain\'92t got a soul of his own, but on\'92y a piece of a big one\'97an\'92 then\'97\'97\'94 \'93Then what, Tom?\'94 \'93Then it don\'92 matter. Then I\'92ll be all aroun\'92 in the dark. I\'92ll be ever\'92where\'97wherever you look. Wherever they\'92s a ght so hungry people can eat, I\'92ll be there. Wherever they\'92s a cop beatin\'92 up a guy, I\'92ll be there. If Casy knowed, why, I\'92ll be in the way guys yell when they\'92re mad an\'92\'97I\'92ll be in the way kids laugh when they\'92re hungry an\'92 they know supper\'92s ready. An\'92 when our folks eat the stu they raise an\'92 live in the houses they build\'97why, I\'92ll be there. See? God, I\'92m talkin\'92 like Casy. Comes of thinkin\'92 about him so much. Seems like I can see him sometimes.\'94 \'93I don\'92 un\'92erstan\'92,\'94 Ma said. \'93I don\'92 really know.\'94 \'93Me neither,\'94 said Tom. \'93It\'92s jus\'92 stu I been thinkin\'92 about. Get thinkin\'92 a lot when you ain\'92t movin\'92 aroun\'92. You got to get back, Ma.\'94 \'93You take the money then.\'94 He was silent for a moment. \'93Awright,\'94 he said. \'93An\'92, Tom, later\'97when it\'92s blowed over, you\'92ll come back. You\'92ll nd us?\'94 \'93Sure,\'94 he said. \'93Now you better go. Here, gimme your han\'92.\'94 He guided her toward the entrance. Her ngers clutched his wrist. He swept the vines aside and followed her out. \'93Go up to the eld till you come to a sycamore on the edge, an\'92 then cut acrost the stream. Good-by.\'94 \'93Good-by,\'94 she said, and she walked quickly away. Her eyes were wet and burning, but she did not cry. Her footsteps were loud and careless on the leaves as she went through the brush. And as she went, out of the dim sky the rain began to fall, big drops and few, splashing on the dry leaves heavily. Ma stopped and stood still in the dripping thicket. She turned about\'97took three steps back toward the mound of vines; and then she turned quickly and went back toward the boxcar camp. She went straight out to the culvert and climbed up on the road. The rain had passed now, but the sky was overcast. Behind her on the road she heard footsteps, and she turned nervously. The blinking of a dim ashlight played on the road. Ma turned back and started for home. In a moment a man caught up with her. Politely, he kept his light on the ground and did not play it in her face. \'93Evenin\'92,\'94 he said. Ma said, \'93Howdy.\'94 \'93Looks like we might have a little rain.\'94 \'93I hope