ck?\'94 \'93Why, sure. I walked a piece with the fella. He was comin\'92 to get pickers.\'94 \'93Cotton\'92s nearly gone. Purty thin, these here seconds. Gonna be hard to make a wage on the seconds. Got her pretty clean the fust time.\'94 \'93Your folks could maybe ride with us,\'94 Ma said. \'93Split the gas.\'94 \'93Well\'97that\'92s frien\'92ly of you, ma\'92am.\'94 \'93Saves us both,\'94 said Ma. Pa said, \'93Mr. Wainwright\'97he\'92s got a worry he come to us about. We was a-talkin\'92 her over.\'94 \'93What\'92s the matter?\'94 Wainwright looked down at the oor. \'93Our Aggie,\'94 he said. \'93She\'92s a big girl\'97near sixteen, an\'92 growed up.\'94 \'93Aggie\'92s a pretty girl,\'94 said Ma. \'93Listen \'92im out,\'94 Pa said. \'93Well, her an\'92 your boy Al, they\'92re a-walkin\'92 out ever\'92 night. An\'92 Aggie\'92s a good healthy girl that oughta have a husban\'92, else she might git in trouble. We never had no trouble in our family. But what with us bein\'92 so poor o, now, Mis\'92 Wainwright an\'92 me, we got to worryin\'92. S\'92pose she got in trouble?\'94 Ma rolled down a mattress and sat on it. \'93They out now?\'94 she asked. \'93Always out,\'94 said Wainwright. \'93Ever\'92 night.\'94 \'93Hm. Well, Al\'92s a good boy. Kinda ggers he\'92s a dung-hill rooster these days, but he\'92s a good steady boy. I couldn\'92 want for a better boy.\'94 \'93Oh, we ain\'92t complainin\'92 about Al as a fella! We like him. But what scares Mis\'92 Wainwright an\'92 me\'97well, she\'92s a growed-up woman-girl. An\'92 what if we go away, or you go away, an\'92 we nd out Aggie\'92s in trouble? We ain\'92t had no shame in our family.\'94 Ma said softly, \'93We\'92ll try an\'92 see that we don\'92t put no shame on you.\'94 He stood up quickly. \'93Thank you, ma\'92am. Aggie\'92s a growed-up woman-girl. She\'92s a good girl\'97jes\'92 as nice an\'92 good. We\'92ll sure thank you, ma\'92am, if you\'92ll keep shame from us. It ain\'92t Aggie\'92s fault. She\'92s growed 