e water crept over the oor. Pa and Ma, Al and Uncle John, each at a corner, lifted Rose of Sharon\'92s mattress, with the girl on it, and put it on top of the pile. And the girl protested, \'93I can walk. I\'92m awright.\'94 And the water crept over the oor, a thin lm of it. Rose of Sharon whispered to Ma, and Ma put her hand under the blanket and felt her breast and nodded. In the other end of the boxcar, the Wainwrights were pounding, building a platform for themselves. The rain thickened, and then passed away. Ma looked down at her feet. The water was half an inch deep on the car oor by now. \'93You, Ruthie\'97Winel\'92!\'94 she called distractedly. \'93Come get on top of the pile. You\'92ll get cold.\'94 She saw them safely up, sitting awkwardly beside Rose of Sharon. Ma said suddenly, \'93We got to git out.\'94 \'93We can\'92t,\'94 Pa said. \'93Like Al says, all our stu\'92s here. We\'92ll pull o the boxcar door an\'92 make more room to set on.\'94 The family huddled on the platforms, silent and fretful. The water was six inches deep in the car before the ood spread evenly over the embankment and moved into the cotton eld on the other side. During that day and night the men slept soddenly, side by side on the boxcar door. And Ma lay close to Rose of Sharon. Sometimes Ma whispered to her and sometimes sat up quietly, her face brooding. Under the blanket she hoarded the remains of the store bread. The rain had become intermittent now\'97little wet squalls and quiet times. On the morning of the second day Pa splashed through the camp and came back with ten potatoes in his pockets. Ma watched him sullenly while he chopped out part of the inner wall of the car, built a re, and scooped water into a pan. The family ate the steaming boiled potatoes with their ngers. And when this last food was gone, they stared at the gray water; and in the night they did not lie down for a long time. When the morning came they awakened nervously. Rose of Sharon whispered to Ma. Ma nod