In the afternoon Samuel and Adam rode over the land. The wind came up as it did every afternoon, and the yellow dust ran into the sky. \
\'93Oh, it\'92s a good piece,\'94 Samuel cried. \'93It\'92s a rare piece of land.\'94 \
\'93Seems to me it\'92s blowing away bit by bit,\'94 Adam observed. \
\'93No, it\'92s just moving over a little. You lose some to the James ranch but you get some from the Southeys.\'94 \
\'93Well, I don\'92t like the wind. Makes me nervous.\'94 \
\'93Nobody likes wind for very long. It makes animals nervous and restless too. I don\'92t know whether you noticed, but a little farther up the valley they\'92re planting windbreaks of gum trees. Eucalyptus\'97comes from Australia. They say the gums grow ten feet a year. Why don\'92t you try a few rows and see what happens? In time they should back up the wind a little, and they make grand firewood.\'94 \
