\'93That\'92s good,\'94 said Adam. \'93I wouldn\'92t mind the wind if it worked for me. And if I could get water I might plant alfalfa.\'94 \
\'93It\'92s never brought much of a price.\'94 \
\'93I wasn\'92t thinking of that. Few weeks ago I took a drive up around Greenfield and Gonzales. Some Swiss have moved in there. They\'92ve got nice little dairy herds, and they get four crops of alfalfa a year.\'94 \
\'93I heard about them. They brought in Swiss cows.\'94 Adam\'92s face was bright with plans. \'93That\'92s what I want to do. Sell butter and cheese and feed the milk to pigs.\'94 \
\'93You\'92re going to bring credit to the valley,\'94 Samuels said. \'93You\'92re going to be a real joy to the future.\'94 \
\'93If I can get water.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ll get you water if there\'92s any to be got. I\'92ll find it. I brought my magic wand.\'94 He patted a forked stick tied to his saddle. \
Adam pointed to the left where a wide flat place was covered with a low growth of sagebrush. \'93Now then,\'94 he said, \'93thirty-six acres and almost level as a floor. I put an auger down. Topsoil averages three and a half feet, sand on top and loam within plow reach. Think you could get water there?\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Samuel said. \'93I\'92ll see.\'94 He dismounted, handed his reins to Adam, and untied his forked wand. He took the forks in his two hands and walked slowly, his arms out and stretched before him and the wand tip up. His steps took a zigzag course. Once he frowned and backed up a few steps, then shook his head and went on. Adam rode slowly behind, leading the other horse. \
Adam kept his eyes on the stick. He saw it quiver and then jerk a little, as though an invisible fish were tugging at a line. Samuel\'92s face was taut with attention. He continued on until the point of the wand seemed to be pulled strongly downward against his straining arms. He made a slow circle, broke off a piece of sagebrush, and dropped it on the ground. He moved well outside his circle, held up his stick again, and moved inward toward his marker. As he came near it, the point of the stick was drawn down again. Samuel sighed and relaxed and dropped his wand on the ground. \'93I can get water here,\'94 he said. \'93And not very deep. The pull was strong, plenty of water.\'94 \
\'93Good,\'94 said Adam. \'93I want to show you a couple more places.\'94 \
Samuel whittled out a stout piece of sagewood and drove it into the soil. He made a split on the top and fitted a crosspiece on for a mark. Then he kicked the brittle brush down in the area so he could find his marker again. \
On a second try three hundred yards away the wand seemed nearly torn downward out of his hands. \'93Now there\'92s a whole world of water here,\'94 he said. \
The third try was not so productive. After half an hour he had only the slightest sign. \
