\'93It looks like tool steel,\'94 said Tom. \'93We haven\'92t got anything that can touch it.\'94 Then he saw the faraway joyous look on his father\'92s face and a shiver of shared delight came to him. The Hamilton children loved it when their father\'92s mind went free. Then the world was peopled with wonders. \
Samuel said, \'93Metal, you say. You think, steel. Tom, I\'92m going to make a guess and then I\'92m going to get an assay. Now hear my guess\'97and remember it. I think we\'92ll find nickel in it, and silver maybe, and carbon and manganese. How I would like to dig it up! It\'92s in sea sand. That\'92s what we\'92ve been getting.\'94 \
Tom said, \'93Say, what do you think it is with\'97nickel and silver\'97\'94 \
\'93It must have been long thousand centuries ago,\'94 Samuel said, and his sons knew he was seeing it. \'93Maybe it was all water here\'97an inland sea with the seabirds circling and crying. And it would have been a pretty thing if it happened at night. There would come a line of light and then a pencil of white light and then a tree of blinding light drawn in a long arc from heaven. Then there\'92d be a great water spout and a big mushroom of steam. And your ears would be staggered by the sound because the soaring cry of its coming would be on you at the same time the water exploded. And then it would be black night again, because of the blinding light. And gradually you\'92d see the killed fish coming up, showing silver in the starlight, and the crying birds would come to eat them. It\'92s a lonely, lovely thing to think about, isn\'92t it?\'94 \
He made them see it as he always did. \
Tom said softly, \'93You think it\'92s a meteorite, don\'92t you?\'94 \
\'93That I do. and we can prove it by assay.\'94 \
Joe said eagerly, \'93Let\'92s dig it up.\'94 \
\'93You dig it, Joe, while we bore for water.\'94 \
Tom said seriously, \'93If the assay showed enough nickel and silver, wouldn\'92t it pay to mine it?\'94 \
\'93You\'92re my own son,\'94 said Samuel. \'93We don\'92t know whether it\'92s big as a house or little as a hat.\'94 \
\'93But we could probe down and see.\'94 \
\'93That we could if we did it secretly and hid our thinking under a pot.\'94 \
\'93Why, what do you mean?\'94 \
\'93Now, Tom, have you no kindness toward your mother? We give her enough trouble, son. She\'92s told me plain that if I spend any more money patenting things, she\'92ll give us trouble to remember. Have pity on her! Can\'92t you see her shame when they ask her what we\'92re doing? She\'92s a truthful \
woman, your mother. She\'92d have to say, \'91They\'92re at digging up a star.\'92 \'94 He laughed happily. \'93She\'92d never live it down. And she\'92d make us smart. No pies for three months.\'94 \
Tom said, \'93We can\'92t get through it. We\'92ll have to move to another place.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ll put some blasting powder down,\'94 said his father, \'93and if that doesn\'92t crack it aside we\'92ll start a new hole.\'94 He stood up. \'93I\'92ll have to go home for powder and to sharpen the drill. Why don\'92t you boys ride along with me and we\'92ll give Mother a surprise so that she\'92ll cook the whole night and complain. That way she\'92ll dissemble her pleasure.\'94 \
Joe said, \'93Somebody\'92s coming, coming fast.\'94 And indeed they could see a horseman riding toward them at full gallop, but a curious horseman who flopped about on his mount like a tied chicken. When he came a little closer they saw that it was Lee, his elbows waving like wings, his queue lashing about like a snake. It was surprising that he stayed on at all and still drove the horse at full tilt. He pulled up, breathing heavily. \'93Missy Adam say come! Missy Cathy bad \'97come quick. Missy yell, scream.\'94 \
Samuel said, \'93Hold on, Lee. When did it start?\'94 \
\'93Mebbe bleakfus time.\'94 \
\'93All right. Calm yourself. How is Adam?\'94 \
\'93Missy Adam clazy. Cly\'97laugh\'97make vomit.\'94 \
\'93Sure,\'94 said Samuel. \'93These new fathers. I was one once. Tom, throw a saddle on for me, will you?\'94 \
Joe said, \'93What is it?\'94 \
\'93Why, Mrs. Trask is about to have her baby. I told Adam I\'92d stand by.\'94 \
\'93You?\'94 Joe asked. \
Samuel leveled his eyes on his youngest son. \'93I brought both of you into the world,\'94 he said. \'93And you\'92ve given no evidence you think I did a bad service to the world. Tom, you \
get all the tools gathered up. And go back to the ranch and sharpen the metal. Bring back the box of powder that\'92s on the shelf in the tool shed, and go easy with it as you love your arms and legs. Joe, I want you to stay here and look after things.\'94 \
Joe said plaintively, \'93But what will I do here alone?\'94 \
Samuel was silent for a moment. Then he said, \'93Joe, do you love me?\'94 \
\'93Why, sure.\'94 \
\'93If you heard I\'92d committed some great crime would you turn me over to the police?\'94 \
\'93What are you talking about?\'94 \'93Would you?\'94\uc0\u8232 \'93No.\'94 \
\'93All right then. In my basket, under my clothes, you\'92ll find two books\'97new, so be gentle with them. It\'92s two volumes by a man the world is going to hear from. You can start reading if you want and it will raise up your lid a little. It\'92s called The Principles of Psychology and it\'92s by an Eastern man named William James. No relative to the train robber. And, Joe, if you ever let on about the books I\'92ll run you off the ranch. If your mother ever found out I spent the money on them she\'92d run me off the ranch.\'94 \
Tom led a saddled horse to him. \'93Can I read it next?\'94 \
\'93Yes,\'94 said Samuel, and he slipped his leg lightly over the saddle. \'93Come on, Lee.\'94 \
The Chinese wanted to break into a gallop but Samuel restrained him. \'93Take it easy, Lee. Birthing takes longer than you think, mostly.\'94 \
For a time they rode in silence, and then Lee said, \'93I\'92m sorry you bought those books. I have the condensed form, in one volume, the textbook. You could have borrowed it.\'94 \
\'93Have you now? Do you have many books?\'94 \
\'93Not many here\'97thirty or forty. But you\'92re welcome to any of them you haven\'92t read.\'94 \
\'93Thank you, Lee. And you may be sure I\'92ll look the first moment I can. You know, you could talk to my boys. Joe\'92s a little flighty but Tom\'92s all right and it would do him good.\'94 \
\'93It\'92s a hard bridge to cross, Mr. Hamilton. Makes me timid to talk to a new person, but I\'92ll try if you say so.\'94 \
They walked the horses rapidly toward the little draw of the Trask place. Samuel said, \'93Tell me, how is it with the mother?\'94 \
\'93I\'92d rather you saw for yourself and thought for yourself,\'94 Lee said. \'93You know when a man lives alone as much as I do, his mind can go off on an irrational tangent just because his social world is out of kilter.\'94 \
\'93Yes, I know. But I\'92m not lonely and I\'92m on a tangent too. But maybe not the same one.\'94 \
\'93You don\'92t think I imagine it then?\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know what it is, but I\'92ll tell you for your reassurance that I\'92ve a sense of strangeness.\'94 \
\'93I guess that\'92s all it is with me too,\'94 said Lee. He smiled. \'93I\'92ll tell you how far it got with me though. Since I\'92ve come here I find myself thinking of Chinese fairy tales my father told me. We Chinese have a well-developed demonology.\'94 \
\'93You think she is a demon?\'94 \
\'93Of course not,\'94 said Lee. \'93I hope I\'92m a little beyond such silliness. I don\'92t know what it is. You know, Mr. Hamilton, a servant develops an ability to taste the wind and judge the climate of the house he works in. And there\'92s a strangeness here. Maybe that\'92s what makes me remember my father\'92s demons.\'94 \
\'93Did your father believe in them?\'94 \
\'93Oh, no. He thought I should know the background. You Occidentals perpetuate a good many myths too.\'94 \
Samuel said, \'93Tell me what happened to set you off. This morning, I mean.\'94 \
\'93If you weren\'92t coming I would try,\'94 said Lee. \'93But I would rather not. You can see for yourself. I may be crazy. Of course Mr. Adam is strung so tight he may snap like a banjo string.\'94 \
\'93Give me a little hint. It might save time. What did she do?\'94 \
\'93Nothing. That\'92s just it. Mr. Hamilton, I\'92ve been at births before, a good many of them, but this is something new to me.\'94 \
\'93How?\'94 \
\'93It\'92s\'97well\'97I\'92ll tell you the one thing I can think of. This is much more like a bitter, deadly combat than a birth.\'94 \
As they rode into the draw and under the oak trees Samuel said, \'93I hope you haven\'92t got me in a state, Lee. It\'92s a strange day, and I don\'92t know why.\'94 \
\'93No wind,\'94 said Lee. \'93It\'92s the first day in a month when there hasn\'92t been wind in the afternoon.\'94 \
\'93That\'92s so. You know I\'92ve been so close to the details I\'92ve paid no attention to the clothing of the day. First we find a buried star and now we go to dig up a mint-new human.\'94 He looked up through the oak branches at the yellow-lit hills. \'93What a beautiful day to be born in!\'94 he said. \'93If signs have their fingers on a life, it\'92s a sweet life coming. And, Lee, if Adam plays true, he\'92ll be in the way. Stay close, will you? In case I need something. Look, the men, the carpenters, are sitting under that tree.\'94 \
\'93Mr. Adam stopped the work. He thought the hammering might disturb his wife.\'94 \
Samuel said, \'93You stay close. That sounds like Adam playing true. He doesn\'92t know his wife probably couldn\'92t hear God Himself beating a tattoo on the sky.\'94 \
The workmen sitting under the tree waved to him. \'93How do, Mr. Hamilton. How\'92s your family?\'94 \
\'93Fine, fine. Say, isn\'92t that Rabbit Holman? Where\'92ve you been, Rabbit?\'94 \
\'93Went prospecting, Mr. Hamilton.\'94 \
\'93Find anything, Rabbit?\'94 \
\'93Hell, Mr. Hamilton, I couldn\'92t even find the mule I went out with.\'94 \
They rode on toward the house. Lee said quickly, \'93If you ever get a minute, I\'92d like to show you something.\'94 \
\'93What is it, Lee?\'94 \
\'93Well, I\'92ve been trying to translate some old Chinese poetry into English. I\'92m not sure it can be done. Will you take a look?\'94 \
\'93I\'92d like to, Lee. Why, that would be a treat for me.\'94 \
