Bordoni\'92s white frame house was very quiet, almost broodingly quiet, and the shades were pulled down. Samuel dismounted at the stoop, untied his bulging saddlebags, and gave his horse to Lee. He knocked and got no answer and went in. It was dusky in the living room after the outside light. He looked in the kitchen, scrubbed to the wood grain by Lee. A gray stoneware pilon coffeepot grunted on the back of the stove. Samuel tapped lightly on the bedroom door and went in. \
It was almost pitch-black inside, for not only were the shades down but blankets were tacked over the windows. Cathy was lying in the big four-poster bed, and Adam sat beside her, his face buried in the coverlet. He raised his head and looked blindly out. \
Samuel said pleasantly, \'93Why are you sitting in the dark?\'94 \
Adam\'92s voice was hoarse. \'93She doesn\'92t want the light. It hurts her eyes.\'94 \
Samuel walked into the room and authority grew in him with each step. \'93There will have to be lieht,\'94 he said. \'93She can close her eyes. I\'92ll tie a black cloth over them if she wants.\'94 He moved to the window and grasped the blanket to pull it down, but Adam was upon him before he could yank. \
\'93Leave it. The light hurts her,\'94 he said fiercely. \
Samuel turned on him. \'93Now, Adam, I know what you feel. I promised you I\'92d take care of things, and I will. I only hope one of those things isn\'92t you.\'94 He pulled the blanket down and rolled up the shade to let the golden afternoon light in. \
Cathy made a little mewing sound from the bed, and Adam went to her. \'93Close your eyes, dear. I\'92ll put a cloth over your eyes.\'94 \
Samuel dropped his saddlebags in a chair and stood beside the bed. \'93Adam,\'94 he said firmly, \'93I\'92m going to ask you to go out of the room and to stay out.\'94 \
\'93No, I can\'92t. Why?\'94 \
\'93Because I don\'92t want you in the way. It\'92s considered a sweet practice for you to get drunk.\'94 \
\'93I couldn\'92t.\'94 \
Samuel said, \'93Anger\'92s a slow thing in me and disgust is slower, but I can taste the beginnings of both of them. You\'92ll get out of the room and give me no trouble or I\'92ll go away and you\'92ll have a basket of trouble.\'94 \
Adam went finally, and from the doorway Samuel called, \'93And I don\'92t want you bursting in if you hear anything. You wait for me to come out.\'94 He closed the door, noticed there \
was a key in the lock, and turned it. \'93He\'92s an upset, vehement man,\'94 he said. \'93He loves you.\'94 \
He had not looked at her closely until now. And he saw true hatred in her eyes, unforgiving, murderous hatred. \
\'93It\'92ll be over before long, dearie. Now tell me, has the water broke?\'94 \
Her hostile eyes glared at him and her lips raised snarling from her little teeth. She did not answer him. \
He stared at her. \'93I did not come by choice except as a friend,\'94 he said. \'93It\'92s not a pleasure to me, young woman. I don\'92t know your trouble and minute by minute I don\'92t care. Maybe I can save you some pain\'97who knows? I\'92m going to ask you one more question. If you don\'92t answer, if you put that snarling look on me, I\'92m going out and leave you to welter.\'94 \
The words struck into her understanding like lead shot dropping in water. She made a great effort. And it gave him a shivering to see her face change, the steel leave her eyes, the lips thicken from line to bow, and the corners turn up. He noticed a movement of her hands, the fists unclench and the fingers turn pinkly upward. Her face became young and innocent and bravely hurt. It was like one magic-lantern slide taking the place of another. \
She said softly, \'93The water broke at dawn.\'94 \'93That\'92s better. Have you had hard labor?\'94 \'93Yes.\'94\uc0\u8232 \'93How far apart?\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94\uc0\u8232 \'93Well, I\'92ve been in this room fifteen minutes.\'94\u8232 \'93I\'92ve had two little ones\'97no big ones since you came.\'94 \'93Fine. Now where\'92s your linen?\'94\u8232 \'93In that hamper over there.\'94 \
\'93You\'92ll be all right, dearie,\'94 he said gently. \
He opened his saddlebags and took out a thick rope covered with blue velvet and looped at either end. On the velvet hundreds of little pink flowers were embroidered. \'93Liza sent you her pulling rope to use,\'94 he said. \'93She made it when our first-born was preparing. What with our children and friends\'92, this rope has pulled a great number of people into the world.\'94 He slipped one of the loops over each of the footposts of the bed. \
Suddenly her eyes glazed and her back arched like a spring and the blood started to her cheeks. He waited for her cry or scream and looked apprehensively at the closed door. But there was no scream\'97only a series of grunting squeals. After a few seconds her body relaxed and the hatefulness was back in her face. \
The labor struck again. \'93There\'92s a dear,\'94 he said soothingly. \'93Was it one or two? I don\'92t know. The more you see, the more you learn no two are alike. I\'92d better get my hands washed.\'94 \
Her head threshed from side to side. \'93Good, good, my darling,\'94 he said. \'93I think it won\'92t be long till your baby\'92s here.\'94 He put his hand on her forehead where her scar showed dark and angry. \'93How did you get the hurt on your head?\'94 he asked. \
Her head jerked up and her sharp teeth fastened on his hand across the back and up into the palm near the little finger. He cried out in pain and tried to pull his hand away, but her jaw was set and her head twisted and turned, mangling his hand the way a terrier worries a sack. A shrill snarling came from her set teeth. He slapped her on the cheek and it had no effect. Automatically he did what he would have done to stop a dog fight. His left hand went to her throat and he cut off her wind. She struggled and tore at his hand before her jaws unclenched and he pulled his hand \
free. The flesh was torn and bleeding. He stepped back from the bed and looked at the damage her teeth had done. He looked at her with fear. And when he looked, her face was calm again and young and innocent. \
\'93I\'92m sorry,\'94 she said quickly. \'93Oh, I\'92m sorry.\'94 Samuel shuddered.\uc0\u8232 \'93It was the pain,\'94 she said. \
Samuel laughed shortly. \'93I\'92ll have to muzzle you, I guess,\'94 he said. \'93A collie bitch did the same to me once.\'94 He saw the hatred look out of her eyes for a second and then retreat. \
Samuel said, \'93Have you got anything to put on it? Humans are more poisonous than snakes.\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know.\'94 \
\'93Well, have you got any whisky? I\'92ll pour some whisky on it.\'94 \
\'93In the second drawer.\'94 \
He splashed whisky on his bleeding hand and kneaded the flesh against the alcohol sting. A strong quaking was in his stomach and a sickness rose up against his eyes. He took a swallow of whisky to steady himself. He dreaded to look back at the bed. \'93My hand won\'92t be much good for a while,\'94 he said. \
Samuel told Adam afterward, \'93She must be made of whalebone. The birth happened before I was ready. Popped like a seed. I\'92d not the water ready to wash him. Why, she didn\'92t even touch the pulling rope to bear down. Pure whalebone, she is.\'94 He tore at the door, called Lee and demanded warm water. Adam came charging into the room. \'93A boy!\'94 Samuel cried. \'93You\'92ve got a boy! Easy,\'94 he said, for Adam had seen the mess in the bed and a green was rising in his face. \
Samuel said, \'93Send Lee in here. And you, Adam, if you still have the authority to tell your hands and feet what to do, get to the kitchen and make me some coffee. And see the lamps are filled and the chimneys clean.\'94 \
Adam turned like a zombie and left the room. In a moment Lee looked in. Samuel pointed to the bundle in a laundry basket. \'93Sponge him off in warm water, Lee. Don\'92t let a draft get on him. Lord! I wish Liza were here. I can\'92t do everything at once.\'94 \
He turned back to the bed. \'93Now, dearie, I\'92ll get you cleaned up.\'94 \
Cathy was bowed again, snarling in her pain. \'93It\'92ll be over in a little,\'94 he said. \'93Takes a little time for the residue. And you\'92re so quick. Why, you didn\'92t even have to pull on Liza\'92s rope.\'94 He saw something, stared, and went quickly to work. \'93Lord God in Heaven, it\'92s another one!\'94 \
He worked fast, and as with the first the birth was incredibly quick. And again Samuel tied the cord. Lee took the second baby, washed it, wrapped it, and put it in the basket. \
Samuel cleaned the mother and shifted her gently while he changed the linen on the bed. He found in himself a reluctance to look in her face. He worked as quickly as he could, for his bitten hand was stiffening. He drew a clean white sheet up to her chin and raised her to slip a fresh pillow under her head. At last he had to look at her. \
Her golden hair was wet with perspiration but her face had changed. It was stony, expressionless. At her throat the pulse fluttered visibly. \
\'93You have two sons,\'94 Samuel said. \'93Two fine sons. They aren\'92t alike. Each one born separate in his own sack.\'94 \
She inspected him coldly and without interest. Samuel said, \'93I\'92ll show your boys to you.\'94 \
\'93No,\'94 she said without emphasis.\uc0\u8232 \'93Now, dearie, don\'92t you want to see your sons?\'94 \'93No. I don\'92t want them.\'94 \
\'93Oh, you\'92ll change. You\'92re tired now, but you\'92ll change. And I\'92ll tell you now\'97this birth was quicker and easier than I\'92ve seen ever in my life.\'94 \
The eyes moved from his face. \'93I don\'92t want them. I want you to cover the windows and take the light away.\'94 \
\'93It\'92s weariness. In a few days you\'92ll feel so different you won\'92t remember.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ll remember. Go away. Take them out of the room. Send Adam in.\'94 \
Samuel was caught by her tone. There was no sickness, no weariness, no softness. His words came out without his will. \'93I don\'92t like you,\'94 he said and wished he could gather the words back into his throat and into his mind. But his words had no effect on Cathy. \
\'93Send Adam in,\'94 she said. \
In the little living room Adam looked vaguely at his sons and went quickly into the bedroom and shut the door. In a moment came the sound of tapping. Adam was nailing the blankets over the windows again. \
Lee brought coffee to Samuel. \'93That\'92s a bad-looking hand you have there,\'94 he said. \
\'93I know. I\'92m afraid it\'92s going to give me trouble.\'94 \
\'93Why did she do it?\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know. She\'92s a strange thing.\'94 \
Lee said, \'93Mr. Hamilton, let me take care of that. You could lose an arm.\'94 \
The life went out of Samuel. \'93Do what you want, Lee. A frightened sorrow has closed down over my heart. I wish I were a child so I could cry. I\'92m too old to be afraid like this. \
And I\'92ve not felt such despair since a bird died in my hand by a flowing water long ago.\'94 \
Lee left the room and shortly returned, carrying a small ebony box carved with twisting dragons. He sat by Samuel and from his box took a wedge-shaped Chinese razor. \'93It will hurt,\'94 he said softly. \
\'93I\'92ll try to bear it, Lee.\'94 \
The Chinese bit his lips, feeling the inflicted pain in himself while he cut deeply into the hand, opened the flesh around the toothmarks front and back, and trimmed the ragged flesh away until good red blood flowed from every wound. He shook a bottle of yellow emulsion labeled Hall\'92s Cream Salve and poured it into the deep cuts. He saturated a handkerchief with the salve and wrapped the hand. Samuel winced and gripped the chair arm with his good hand. \
\'93It\'92s mostly carbolic acid,\'94 Lee said. \'93You can smell it.\'94 \
\'93Thank you, Lee. I\'92m being a baby to knot up like this.\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t think I could have been so quiet,\'94 said Lee. \'93I\'92ll get you another cup of coffee.\'94 \
He came back with two cups and sat down by Samuel. \'93I think I\'92ll go away,\'94 he said. \'93I never went willingly to a slaughter house.\'94 \
Samuel stiffened. \'93What do you mean?\'94 \
\'93I don\'92t know. The words came out.\'94 \
Samuel shivered. \'93Lee, men are fools. I guess I hadn\'92t thought about it, but Chinese men are fools too.\'94 \
\'93What made you doubt it?\'94 \
\'93Oh, maybe because we think of strangers as stronger and better than we are.\'94 \
\'93What do you want to say?\'94 \
Samuel said, \'93Maybe the foolishness is necessary, the dragon fighting, the boasting, the pitiful courage to be constantly knocking a chip off God\'92s shoulder, and the childish cowardice that makes a ghost of a dead tree beside a darkening road. Maybe that\'92s good and necessary, but\'97\'94 \
\'93What do you want to say?\'94 Lee repeated patiently. \
\'93I thought some wind had blown up the embers in my foolish mind,\'94 Samuel said. \'93And now I hear in your voice that you have it too. I feel wings over this house. I feel a dreadfulness coming.\'94 \
\'93I feel it too.\'94 \
\'93I know you do, and that makes me take less than my usual comfort in my foolishness. This birth was too quick, too easy\'97like a cat having kittens. And I fear for these kittens. I have dreadful thoughts gnawing to get into my brain.\'94 \
\'93What do you want to say?\'94 Lee asked a third time. \
\'93I want my wife,\'94 Samuel cried. \'93No dreams, no ghosts, no foolishness. I want her here. They say miners take canaries into the pits to test the air. Liza has no truck with foolishness. And, Lee, if Liza sees a ghost, it\'92s a ghost and not a fragment of a dream. If Liza feels trouble we\'92ll bar the doors.\'94 \
Lee got up and went to the laundry basket and looked down at the babies. He had to peer close, for the light was going fast. \'93They\'92re sleeping,\'94 he said. \
\'93They\'92ll be squalling soon enough. Lee, will you hitch up the rig and drive to my place for Liza? Tell her I need her here. If Tom\'92s still there, tell him to mind the place. If not, I\'92ll send him in the morning. And if Liza doesn\'92t want to come, tell her we need a woman\'92s hand here and a woman\'92s clear eyes. She\'92ll know what you mean.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ll do it,\'94 said Lee. \'93Maybe we\'92re scaring each other, like two children in the dark.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ve thought of that,\'94 Samuel said. \'93And Lee, tell her I hurt my hand at the well head. Do not, for God\'92s sake, tell her how it happened.\'94 \
\'93I\'92ll get some lamps lit and then I\'92ll go,\'94 said Lee. \'93It will be a great relief to have her here.\'94 \
\'93That it will, Lee. That it will. She\'92ll let some light into this cellar hole.\'94 \
After Lee drove away in the dark Samuel picked up a lamp in his left hand. He had to set it on the floor to turn the knob of the bedroom door. The room was in pitch-blackness, and the yellow lamplight streamed upward and did not light the bed. \
Cathy\'92s voice came strong and edged from the bed. \'93Shut the door. I do not want the light. Adam, go out! I want to be in the dark\'97alone.\'94 \
Adam said hoarsely, \'93I want to stay with you.\'94 \
\'93I do not want you.\'94 \
\'93I will stay.\'94 \
\'93Then stay. But don\'92t talk any more. Please close the door and take the lamp away.\'94 \
Samuel went back to the living room. He put the lamp on the table by the laundry basket and looked in on the small sleeping faces of the babies. Their eyes were pinched shut and they sniffled a little in discomfort at the light. Samuel put his forefinger down and stroked the hot foreheads. One of the twins opened his mouth and yawned prodigiously and settled back to sleep. Samuel moved the lamp and then went to the front door and opened it and stepped outside. The evening star was so bright that it seemed to flare and crumple as it sank toward the western mountains. The air was still, and Samuel could smell the day-heated sage. The night was very dark. Samuel started when he heard a voice speaking out of the blackness. \
\'93How is she?\'94 \
\'93Who is it?\'94 Samuel demanded. \
\'93It\'92s me, Rabbit.\'94 The man emerged and took form in the light from the doorway. \
\'93The mother, Rabbit? Oh, she\'92s fine.\'94 \
\'93Lee said twins.\'94 \
\'93That\'92s right\'97twin sons. You couldn\'92t want better. I guess Mr. Trask will tear the river up by the roots now. He\'92ll bring in a crop of candy canes.\'94 \
Samuel didn\'92t know why he changed the subject. \'93Rabbit, do you know what we bored into today? A meteorite.\'94 \
\'93What\'92s that, Mr. Hamilton?\'94 \
\'93A shooting star that fell a million years ago.\'94 \
\'93You did? Well, think of that! How did you hurt your hand?\'94 \
\'93I almost said on a shooting star.\'94 Samuel laughed. \'93But it wasn\'92t that interesting. I pinched it in the tackle.\'94 \
\'93Bad?\'94 \
\'93No, not bad.\'94 \
\'93Two boys,\'94 said Rabbit. \'93My old lady will be jealous.\'94 \
\'93Will you come inside and sit, Rabbit?\'94 \
