A war comes always to someone else. In Salinas we were aware that the United States was the greatest and most powerful nation in the world. Every American was a rifleman by birth, and one American was worth ten or twenty foreigners in a fight. \
Pershing\'92s expedition into Mexico after Villa had exploded one of our myths for a little while. We had truly believed that Mexicans can\'92t shoot straight and besides were lazy and stupid. When our own Troop C came wearily back from the border they said that none of this was true. Mexicans could shoot straight, goddam it! And Villa\'92s horsemen had outridden and outlasted our town boys. The two evenings a month of training had not toughened them very much. And last, the Mexicans seemed to have outthought and outambushed Black Jack Pershing. When the Mexicans were joined by their ally, dysentery, it was godawful. Some of our boys didn\'92t really feel good again for years. \
Somehow we didn\'92t connect Germans with Mexicans. We went right back to our myths. One American was as good as twenty Germans. This being true, we had only to act in a stern manner to bring the Kaiser to heel. He wouldn\'92t dare interfere with our trade\'97but he did. He wouldn\'92t stick out his neck and sink our ships\'97and he did. It was stupid, but he did, and so there was nothing for it but to fight him. \
The war, at first anyway, was for other people. We, I, my family and friends, had kind of bleacher seats, and it was pretty exciting. And just as war is always for somebody else, so it is also true that someone else always gets killed. And Mother of God! that wasn\'92t true either. The dreadful \
telegrams began to sneak sorrowfully in, and it was everybody\'92s brother. Here we were, over six thousand miles from the anger and the noise, and that didn\'92t save us. \
It wasn\'92t much fun then. The Liberty Belles could parade in white caps and uniforms of white sharkskin. Our uncle could rewrite his Fourth of July speech and use it to sell bonds. We in high school could wear olive drab and campaign hats and learn the manual of arms from the physics teacher, but Jesus Christ! Marty Hopps dead, the Berges boy, from across the street, the handsome one our little sister was in love with from the time she was three, blown to bits! \
And the gangling, shuffling loose-jointed boys carrying suitcases were marching awkwardly down Main Street to the Southern Pacific Depot. They were sheepish, and the Salinas Band marched ahead of them, playing the \'93Stars and Stripes Forever,\'94 and the families walking along beside them were crying, and the music sounded like a dirge. The draftees wouldn\'92t look at their mothers. They didn\'92t dare. We\'92d never thought the war could happen to us. \
There were some in Salinas who began to talk softly in the poolrooms and the bars. These had private information from a soldier\'97we weren\'92t getting the truth. Our men were being sent in without guns. Troopships were sunk and the government wouldn\'92t tell us. The German army was so far superior to ours that we didn\'92t have a chance. That Kaiser was a smart fellow. He was getting ready to invade America. But would Wilson tell us this? He would not. And usually these carrion talkers were the same ones who had said one American was worth twenty Germans in a scrap\'97the same ones. \
Little groups of British in their outlandish uniforms (but they did look smart) moved about the country, buying everything that wasn\'92t nailed down and paying for it and paying big. A good many of the British purchasing men were \
crippled, but they wore their uniforms just the same. Among other things they bought beans, because beans are easy to transport and they don\'92t spoil and a man can damn well live on them. Beans were twelve and a half cents a pound and hard to find. And farmers wished they hadn\'92t contracted their beans for a lousy two cents a pound above the going price six months ago. \
